# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: ferrite-magnet
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:ferrite-magnet/alnico] The composition of alnico alloys is typically 8–12% Al, 15–26% Ni, 5–24% Co, up to 6% Cu, up to 1% Ti, and the rest is Fe.
[src:ferrite-magnet/alnico] The development of alnico began in 1931, when T.
[src:ferrite-magnet/alnico] Mishima in Japan discovered that an alloy of iron, nickel, and aluminum had a coercivity of 400 oersteds (32 kA/m), double that of the best magnet steels of the time.
[src:ferrite-magnet/alnico] Alnico alloys can be magnetised to produce strong magnetic fields and have a high coercivity (resistance to demagnetization), thus making strong permanent magnets.
[src:ferrite-magnet/alnico] Of the more commonly available magnets, only rare-earth magnets such as neodymium and samarium-cobalt are stronger.
[src:ferrite-magnet/alnico] Alnico magnets produce magnetic field strength at their poles as high as 1500 gauss (0.15 tesla), or about 3000 times the strength of Earth's magnetic field.
[src:ferrite-magnet/alnico] Some alnico brands are isotropic and can be efficiently magnetized in any direction.
[src:ferrite-magnet/alnico] Other types, such as alnico 5 and alnico 8, are anisotropic, each having a preferred direction of magnetization, or orientation.
[src:ferrite-magnet/alnico] Anisotropic alloys generally have greater magnetic capacity in a preferred orientation than isotropic types.
[src:ferrite-magnet/alnico] Alnico's remanence (**B**r) may exceed 12,000 G (1.2 T), its coercivity (**H**c) can be up to 1000 oersteds (80 kA/m), its maximum energy product ((**BH**)max) can be up to 5.5 MG·Oe (44 T·kA/m).
[src:ferrite-magnet/alnico] Therefore, alnico can produce a strong magnetic flux in closed magnetic circuits, but has relatively small resistance against demagnetization.
[src:ferrite-magnet/alnico] The field strength at the poles of any permanent magnet depends very much on the shape and is usually well below the remanence strength of the material.
[src:ferrite-magnet/alnico] Alnico alloys have some of the highest Curie temperatures of any magnetic material, around 800 °C (1,470 °F), although the maximal working temperature is typically limited to around 538 °C (1,000 °F).
[src:ferrite-magnet/alnico] They are the only magnets that have useful magnetism even when heated red-hot.
[src:ferrite-magnet/alnico] This property, as well as its brittleness and high melting point, results from the strong tendency toward order due to intermetallic bonding between aluminum and other constituents.
[src:ferrite-magnet/alnico] They are also one of the most stable magnets if handled properly.
[src:ferrite-magnet/alnico] Alnico magnets are electrically conductive, unlike ceramic magnets.
[src:ferrite-magnet/alnico] Alnico 3 has a melting temperature of 1200 - 1450 °C.
[src:ferrite-magnet/alnico] As of 2018, Alnico magnets cost about 44 USD/kg (US$20/lb) or US$4.30/BHmax.
[src:ferrite-magnet/alnico] Alnico magnets are traditionally classified using numbers assigned by the Magnetic Materials Producers Association (MMPA), for example, alnico 3 or alnico 5.
[src:ferrite-magnet/alnico] These classifications indicate chemical composition and magnetic properties.
[src:ferrite-magnet/alnico] These classification numbers, while still in use, have been deprecated in favor of a new system by the MMPA, which designates alnico magnets based on maximum energy product in megagauss-oersteds and intrinsic coercive force as kilo oersted, as well as an IEC classification system.
[src:ferrite-magnet/alnico] Alnico magnets are produced by casting or sintering processes.
[src:ferrite-magnet/alnico] Cast alnico is produced by conventional methods using resin bonded sand molds, which can be intricate and detailed, thereby allowing for complex shapes to be produced.
[src:ferrite-magnet/alnico] The produced alnico magnet typically has a rough surface.
[src:ferrite-magnet/alnico] This process has higher initial tooling costs for mold creation.
[src:ferrite-magnet/alnico] Sintered alnico magnets are formed using powdered metal manufacturing methods.
[src:ferrite-magnet/alnico] While sintering can also produce a range of shapes, it may not be as suitable for extremely intricate or detailed designs compared to casting.
[src:ferrite-magnet/alnico] Most alnico produced is anisotropic, meaning that during manufacturing the grains are precipitated with their magnetic axes parallel.
[src:ferrite-magnet/alnico] Anisotropic alnico magnets are oriented by heating above a critical temperature and cooling in the presence of a magnetic field.
[src:ferrite-magnet/alnico] Both isotropic and anisotropic alnico require proper heat treatment to develop optimal magnetic properties.
[src:ferrite-magnet/alnico] Without it, alnico's coercivity is about 10 Oe, comparable to technical iron, a soft magnetic material.
[src:ferrite-magnet/alnico] After the heat treatment alnico becomes a composite material, named "precipitation material"—it consists of iron- and cobalt-rich precipitates in a rich-NiAl matrix.
[src:ferrite-magnet/alnico] Alnico's anisotropy is oriented along the desired magnetic axis by applying an external magnetic field to it during the precipitate particle nucleation, which occurs when cooling from 900 °C (1,650 °F) to 800 °C (1,470 °F), near the Curie point.
[src:ferrite-magnet/alnico] There are local anisotropies of different orientations without an external field due to spontaneous magnetization.
[src:ferrite-magnet/alnico] The precipitate structure is a "barrier" against magnetization changes, as it prefers few magnetization states requiring much energy to get the material into any intermediate state.
[src:ferrite-magnet/alnico] Also, a weak magnetic field shifts the magnetization of the matrix phase only and is reversible.
[src:ferrite-magnet/alnico] Alnico magnets are widely used in industrial and consumer applications where strong permanent magnets are needed.
[src:ferrite-magnet/alnico] Examples are electric motors, electric guitar pickups, microphones, sensors, loudspeakers, magnetron tubes, and cow magnets.
[src:ferrite-magnet/alnico] In many applications they are being superseded by rare-earth magnets, whose stronger fields (Br) and larger energy products (B·Hmax) allow smaller-size magnets to be used for a given application.
[src:ferrite-magnet/alnico] The high-temperature resistance of alnico magnets leads to many uses that cannot be filled by less resistant magnets, such as in magnetic stirring hotplates.
[src:ferrite-magnet/aluminum-p01] Chemically, aluminium is a post-transition metal in the boron group; as is common for the group, aluminium forms compounds primarily in the +3 oxidation state.
[src:ferrite-magnet/aluminum-p01] The aluminium cation Al3+ is small and highly charged; as such, it has more polarizing power, and bonds formed by aluminium have a more covalent character.
[src:ferrite-magnet/aluminum-p01] The strong affinity of aluminium for oxygen leads to the common occurrence of its oxides in nature.
[src:ferrite-magnet/aluminum-p01] Aluminium is found on Earth primarily in rocks in the crust, where it is the third-most abundant element after oxygen and silicon, rather than in the mantle, and virtually never as the free metal.
[src:ferrite-magnet/aluminum-p01] It is obtained industrially by mining bauxite, a sedimentary rock rich in aluminium minerals.
[src:ferrite-magnet/aluminum-p01] The discovery of aluminium was announced in 1825 by Danish physicist Hans Christian Ørsted.
[src:ferrite-magnet/aluminum-p01] The first industrial production of aluminium was initiated by French chemist Henri Étienne Sainte-Claire Deville in 1856.
[src:ferrite-magnet/aluminum-p01] Aluminium became much more available to the public with the Hall–Héroult process developed independently by French engineer Paul Héroult and American engineer Charles Martin Hall in 1886, and the mass production of aluminium led to its extensive use in industry and everyday life.
[src:ferrite-magnet/aluminum-p01] In 1954, aluminium became the most produced non-ferrous metal, surpassing copper.
[src:ferrite-magnet/aluminum-p01] In the 21st century, most aluminium was consumed in transportation, engineering, construction, and packaging in the United States, Western Europe, and Japan.
[src:ferrite-magnet/aluminum-p01] The standard atomic weight of aluminium is low in comparison with many other metals, giving it the low density responsible for many of its uses.
[src:ferrite-magnet/aluminum-p01] Despite its prevalence in the environment, no living thing is known to metabolize aluminium salts, but aluminium is well tolerated by plants and animals.
[src:ferrite-magnet/aluminum-p01] Because of the abundance of these salts, the potential for a biological role for them is of interest, and studies are ongoing.
[src:ferrite-magnet/aluminum-p01] Aluminium metal has an appearance ranging from silvery white to dull gray depending on its surface roughness.
[src:ferrite-magnet/aluminum-p01] Aluminium mirrors provides high reflectivity for light in the ultraviolet, visible (on par with silver), and far infrared regions.
[src:ferrite-magnet/aluminum-p01] Aluminium is also good at reflecting solar radiation, although prolonged exposure to sunlight in air can deteriorate the reflectivity of the metal; this may be prevented if aluminium is anodized, which adds a protective layer of oxide on the surface.
[src:ferrite-magnet/aluminum-p01] The density of aluminium is 2.70 g/cm3, about one-third that of steel, much lower than other commonly encountered metals, making aluminium parts easily identifiable through their lightness.
[src:ferrite-magnet/aluminum-p01] Aluminium's low density compared to most other metals arises from the fact that its unit cell size is relatively large in proportion to the number of nucleons.
[src:ferrite-magnet/aluminum-p01] The only lighter metals are the metals of groups 1 and 2, which, apart from beryllium and magnesium, are too reactive for structural use (and beryllium is very toxic).
[src:ferrite-magnet/aluminum-p01] Aluminium is not as strong or stiff as steel, but the low density makes up for this in the aerospace industry and for many other applications where light weight and relatively high strength are crucial.
[src:ferrite-magnet/aluminum-p01] Pure aluminium is quite soft and lacking in strength.
[src:ferrite-magnet/aluminum-p01] In most applications, various aluminium alloys are used instead because of their higher strength and hardness.
[src:ferrite-magnet/aluminum-p01] The yield strength of pure aluminium is 7–11 MPa, while aluminium alloys have yield strengths ranging from 200 MPa to 600 MPa.
[src:ferrite-magnet/aluminum-p01] Aluminium is ductile, with a percent elongation of 50–70%, and malleable allowing it to be easily drawn and extruded; it is also easily machined and cast.
[src:ferrite-magnet/aluminum-p01] Aluminium is an excellent thermal and electrical conductor, and the amount of aluminium required to match the same amperage in copper weighs only half as much.
[src:ferrite-magnet/aluminum-p01] Aluminium is capable of superconductivity, with a superconducting critical temperature of 1.2 kelvin and a critical magnetic field of about 100 gauss (10 milliteslas).
[src:ferrite-magnet/aluminum-p01] It is paramagnetic and thus essentially unaffected by static magnetic fields.
[src:ferrite-magnet/aluminum-p01] However, the high electrical conductivity means that it is strongly affected by alternating magnetic fields through the induction of eddy currents.
[src:ferrite-magnet/aluminum-p01] An aluminium atom has 13 electrons with an electron configuration of [Ne] 3s2 3p1, with three electrons beyond a stable noble gas configuration.
[src:ferrite-magnet/aluminum-p01] Accordingly, the combined first three ionization energies of aluminium are far lower than the fourth ionization energy alone.
[src:ferrite-magnet/aluminum-p01] Such an electron configuration is shared with the other well-characterized members of its group, boron, gallium, indium, and thallium; it is also expected for nihonium.
[src:ferrite-magnet/aluminum-p01] Aluminium can surrender its three outermost electrons in many chemical reactions (see below).
[src:ferrite-magnet/aluminum-p01] The electronegativity of aluminium is 1.61 on the Pauling scale.
[src:ferrite-magnet/aluminum-p01] A free aluminium atom has an atomic radius of 143 pm.
[src:ferrite-magnet/aluminum-p01] With the three outermost electrons removed, the radius shrinks to 39 pm for a 4-coordinated atom or 53.5 pm for a 6-coordinated atom.
[src:ferrite-magnet/aluminum-p01] At standard temperature and pressure, aluminium atoms (when not affected by atoms of other elements) form a face-centered cubic crystal system bound by metallic bonding provided by atoms' outermost electrons; hence, aluminium (at these conditions) is a metal.
[src:ferrite-magnet/aluminum-p01] This crystal system is shared by many other metals, such as lead and copper; the size of a unit cell of aluminium is comparable to that of those other metals.
[src:ferrite-magnet/aluminum-p01] This system, however, is not shared by the other members of its group: boron has ionization energies too high to allow metallization, thallium has a hexagonal close-packed structure, and gallium and indium have unusual structures that are not close-packed like those of aluminium and thallium.
[src:ferrite-magnet/aluminum-p01] The few electrons that are available for metallic bonding in aluminium are a probable cause for it being soft with a low melting point and low electrical resistivity.
[src:ferrite-magnet/aluminum-p01] Aluminium has one stable isotope, 27Al, which comprises virtually all of the naturally-occurring element.
[src:ferrite-magnet/aluminum-p01] This is common for elements with an odd atomic number.
[src:ferrite-magnet/aluminum-p01] It is therefore a mononuclidic element for standard atomic weight, which is determined completely by that isotope.
[src:ferrite-magnet/aluminum-p01] Aluminium is useful in nuclear magnetic resonance (NMR), as its single stable isotope (though quadrupolar) has a high NMR sensitivity.
[src:ferrite-magnet/aluminum-p01] All other isotopes of aluminium are radioactive.
[src:ferrite-magnet/aluminum-p01] The most stable of these is 26Al, with a half-life of 717,000 years.
[src:ferrite-magnet/aluminum-p01] While it was present along with stable 27Al in the interstellar medium from which the Solar System formed (believed to have been produced by stellar nucleosynthesis also), no detectable amount could have survived the time since the formation of the planet.
[src:ferrite-magnet/aluminum-p01] However, minute traces of 26Al are still produced from decay of argon in the atmosphere induced by ionizing radiation of cosmic rays.
[src:ferrite-magnet/aluminum-p01] The ratio of 26Al to 10Be has been used for the radiodating of geological processes over 105 to 106 year time scales, in particular transport, deposition, sediment storage, burial times, and erosion.
[src:ferrite-magnet/aluminum-p01] Most meteorite scientists believe that the energy released by the decay of 26Al was responsible for the melting and differentiation of some asteroids after their formation 4.55 billion years ago.
[src:ferrite-magnet/aluminum-p01] The other known isotopes of aluminium, with mass numbers ranging from 20 to 43, all have half-lives less than 7 minutes, as do the four detected metastable states.
[src:ferrite-magnet/aluminum-p01] Aluminium combines characteristics of pre- and post-transition metals.
[src:ferrite-magnet/aluminum-p01] Since it has few available electrons for metallic bonding, like the heavier group 13 elements, it has the characteristic physical properties of a post-transition metal, with longer-than-expected interatomic distances.
[src:ferrite-magnet/aluminum-p01] Furthermore, as Al3+ is a small and highly charged cation, it is strongly polarizing, and bonding in aluminium compounds tends towards covalency; this behavior is similar to that of beryllium (Be2+), displaying an example of a diagonal relationship.
[src:ferrite-magnet/aluminum-p01] The underlying core of electrons under aluminium's valence shell is that of the preceding noble gas, whereas those of the heavier group 13 elements gallium, indium, thallium, and nihonium also include a filled d-subshell and in some cases a filled f-subshell.
[src:ferrite-magnet/aluminum-p01] Hence, the inner electrons of aluminium shield the valence electrons almost completely, unlike those of the heavier group 13 elements.
[src:ferrite-magnet/aluminum-p01] As such, aluminium is the most electropositive metal in its group, and its hydroxide is in fact more basic than that of gallium.
[src:ferrite-magnet/aluminum-p01] Aluminium also bears minor similarities to boron (a metalloid), which is in the same group: AlX3 compounds are valence isoelectronic to BX3 compounds (they have the same valence electronic structure), and both behave as Lewis acids and readily form adducts.
[src:ferrite-magnet/aluminum-p01] Additionally, one of the main motifs of boron chemistry is regular icosahedral structures, and aluminium forms an important part of many icosahedral quasicrystal alloys, including the Al–Zn–Mg class.
[src:ferrite-magnet/aluminum-p01] Aluminium has a high chemical affinity to oxygen, which renders it suitable for use as a reducing agent in the thermite reaction.
[src:ferrite-magnet/aluminum-p01] A fine powder of aluminium reacts explosively on contact with liquid oxygen; under normal conditions, however, aluminium forms a thin oxide layer (~5 nm at room temperature) that protects the metal from further corrosion by oxygen, water, or dilute acid, a process termed passivation.
[src:ferrite-magnet/aluminum-p01] Aluminium is not attacked by oxidizing acids because of its passivation.
[src:ferrite-magnet/aluminum-p01] This allows aluminium to be used to store reagents such as nitric acid, concentrated sulfuric acid, and some organic acids.
[src:ferrite-magnet/aluminum-p01] In hot, concentrated hydrochloric acid, aluminium reacts with water through evolution of hydrogen, and it reacts in aqueous sodium or potassium hydroxide at room temperature to form aluminates; protective passivation under these conditions is negligible.
[src:ferrite-magnet/aluminum-p01] Aluminium is also corroded by dissolved chlorides, such as common sodium chloride.
[src:ferrite-magnet/aluminum-p01] The oxide layer on aluminium is also destroyed by contact with mercury due to amalgamation or by contact with salts of some electropositive metals.
[src:ferrite-magnet/aluminum-p01] As such, the strongest aluminium alloys are less corrosion-resistant due to galvanic reactions with alloyed copper, and aluminium's corrosion resistance is greatly reduced by aqueous salts, particularly in the presence of dissimilar metals.
[src:ferrite-magnet/aluminum-p01] Aluminium reacts with most nonmetals upon heating, forming compounds such as aluminium nitride (AlN), aluminium sulfide (Al2S3), and the aluminium halides (AlX3).
[src:ferrite-magnet/aluminum-p01] It also forms a wide range of intermetallic compounds involving metals from every group on the periodic table.
[src:ferrite-magnet/aluminum-p01] The vast majority of aluminium compounds, including all aluminium-containing minerals and all commercially significant aluminium compounds, feature aluminium in the oxidation state 3+.
[src:ferrite-magnet/aluminum-p01] The coordination number of such compounds varies, but generally Al3+ is either six- or four-coordinate.
[src:ferrite-magnet/aluminum-p01] Almost all compounds of aluminium(III) are colorless.
[src:ferrite-magnet/aluminum-p01] In aqueous solution, Al3+ exists as the hexa-aqua cation [Al(H2O)6]3+, which has an approximate Ka of 10−5.
[src:ferrite-magnet/aluminum-p01] Such solutions are acidic because this cation can act as a proton donor and progressively hydrolyze until a precipitate of aluminium hydroxide, Al(OH)3, forms.
[src:ferrite-magnet/aluminum-p01] This is useful for clarification of water, since the precipitate nucleates on suspended particles in the water, hence removing them.
[src:ferrite-magnet/aluminum-p01] Increasing the pH even further leads to the hydroxide dissolving again as aluminate, [Al(H2O)2(OH)4]−, is formed.
[src:ferrite-magnet/aluminum-p01] Aluminium hydroxide forms both salts and aluminates and dissolves in acid and alkali, as well as on fusion with acidic and basic oxides.
[src:ferrite-magnet/aluminum-p01] This behavior of Al(OH)3 is termed amphoterism and is characteristic of weakly basic cations that form insoluble hydroxides and whose hydrated species can also donate their protons.
[src:ferrite-magnet/aluminum-p01] One effect of this is that aluminium salts with weak acids are hydrolyzed in water to the aquated hydroxide and the corresponding nonmetal hydride: for example, aluminium sulfide yields hydrogen sulfide.
[src:ferrite-magnet/aluminum-p01] However, some salts like aluminium carbonate exist in aqueous solution but are unstable as such.
[src:ferrite-magnet/aluminum-p01] Only incomplete hydrolysis takes place for salts with strong acids, such as the halides, nitrate, and sulfate.
[src:ferrite-magnet/aluminum-p01] For similar reasons, anhydrous aluminium salts cannot be made by heating their "hydrates": hydrated aluminium chloride is in fact not AlCl3·6H2O but [Al(H2O)6]Cl3, and the Al–O bonds are so strong that heating is not sufficient to break them and form Al–Cl bonds.
[src:ferrite-magnet/aluminum-p01] Unlike the structures of the three heavier trihalides, aluminium fluoride (AlF3) features six-coordinate aluminium, which explains its involatility and insolubility as well as high heat of formation.
[src:ferrite-magnet/aluminum-p01] Each aluminium atom is surrounded by six fluorine atoms in a distorted octahedral arrangement, with each fluorine atom being shared between the corners of two octahedra.
[src:ferrite-magnet/aluminum-p01] Such {AlF6} units also exist in complex fluorides such as cryolite, Na3AlF6.
[src:ferrite-magnet/aluminum-p01] AlF3 melts at 1,290 °C (2,354 °F) and is made by reaction of aluminium oxide with hydrogen fluoride gas at 700 °C (1,300 °F).
[src:ferrite-magnet/aluminum-p01] With heavier halides, the coordination numbers are lower.
[src:ferrite-magnet/aluminum-p01] The other trihalides are dimeric or polymeric with tetrahedral four-coordinate aluminium centers.
[src:ferrite-magnet/aluminum-p01] Aluminium trichloride (AlCl3) has a layered polymeric structure below its melting point of 192.4 °C (378 °F) but transforms on melting to Al2Cl6 dimers.
[src:ferrite-magnet/aluminum-p01] At higher temperatures those increasingly dissociate into trigonal planar AlCl3 monomers similar to the structure of BCl3.
[src:ferrite-magnet/aluminum-p01] Aluminium tribromide and aluminium triiodide form Al2X6 dimers in all three phases and hence do not show such significant changes of properties upon phase change.
[src:ferrite-magnet/aluminum-p01] These materials are prepared by treating aluminium with the halogen.
[src:ferrite-magnet/aluminum-p01] The aluminium trihalides form many addition compounds or complexes.
[src:ferrite-magnet/aluminum-p01] Their Lewis acidic nature makes them useful as catalysts for the Friedel–Crafts reactions.
[src:ferrite-magnet/aluminum-p01] Aluminium trichloride has major industrial uses involving this reaction, such as in the manufacture of anthraquinones and styrene.
[src:ferrite-magnet/aluminum-p01] Aluminium trichloride is also often used as the precursor for many other aluminium compounds and as a reagent for converting nonmetal fluorides into the corresponding chlorides (a transhalogenation reaction).
[src:ferrite-magnet/aluminum-p01] Aluminium forms one stable oxide with the chemical formula Al2O3, commonly called alumina.
[src:ferrite-magnet/aluminum-p01] It can be found in nature in the mineral corundum, the α-alumina phase.
[src:ferrite-magnet/aluminum-p01] Its crystalline form, corundum, is very hard (Mohs hardness 9), has a high melting point of 2,045 °C (3,713 °F), has very low volatility, is chemically inert, and is a good electrical insulator.
[src:ferrite-magnet/aluminum-p01] It is often used in abrasives (such as sandpaper) as a refractory material and in ceramics.
[src:ferrite-magnet/aluminum-p01] It is also the starting material for the electrolytic production of aluminium.
[src:ferrite-magnet/aluminum-p01] Sapphire and ruby are impure corundum contaminated with trace amounts of other metals.
[src:ferrite-magnet/aluminum-p01] The two main oxide-hydroxides, AlO(OH), are boehmite and diaspore.
[src:ferrite-magnet/aluminum-p01] There are three main trihydroxides: bayerite, gibbsite, and nordstrandite, which differ in their crystalline structure (polymorphs).
[src:ferrite-magnet/aluminum-p01] Many other intermediate and related structures are also known.
[src:ferrite-magnet/aluminum-p01] Most of these Al-O-OH systems are produced from ores by a variety of wet processes using acid and bases.
[src:ferrite-magnet/aluminum-p01] Heating the hydroxides leads to the formation of corundum.
[src:ferrite-magnet/aluminum-p01] These materials are of central importance to the production of aluminium and are themselves extremely useful.
[src:ferrite-magnet/aluminum-p01] Some mixed oxide phases are also very useful, such as spinel (MgAl2O4), Na-β-alumina (NaAl11O17), and tricalcium aluminate (Ca3Al2O6), an important mineral phase in Portland cement.
[src:ferrite-magnet/aluminum-p01] The only stable chalcogenides under normal conditions are aluminium sulfide (Al2S3), selenide (Al2Se3), and telluride (Al2Te3).
[src:ferrite-magnet/aluminum-p01] All three are prepared by direct reaction of their elements at about 1,000 °C (1,800 °F) and quickly hydrolyze completely in water to yield aluminium hydroxide and the respective hydrogen chalcogenide.
[src:ferrite-magnet/aluminum-p01] As aluminium is a small atom relative to these chalcogens, these have four-coordinate tetrahedral aluminium with various polymorphs having structures related to wurtzite, with two-thirds of the possible metal sites occupied either in an orderly (α) or random (β) fashion.
[src:ferrite-magnet/aluminum-p01] The sulfide also has a γ form related to γ-alumina and an unusual high-temperature hexagonal form where half the aluminium atoms have tetrahedral four-coordination and the other half have trigonal bipyramidal five-coordination.
[src:ferrite-magnet/aluminum-p01] Four pnictides – aluminium nitride (AlN), aluminium phosphide (AlP), aluminium arsenide (AlAs), and aluminium antimonide (AlSb) – are known.
[src:ferrite-magnet/aluminum-p01] They are all III-V semiconductors isoelectronic to silicon and germanium, all of which but AlN have the zinc blende structure.
[src:ferrite-magnet/aluminum-p01] All four can be made by high-temperature (and possibly high-pressure) direct reaction of their component elements.
[src:ferrite-magnet/aluminum-p01] Aluminium alloys well with most other metals (with the exception of most alkali metals and group 13 metals) and over 150 intermetallics with other metals are known.
[src:ferrite-magnet/aluminum-p01] Preparation involves heating fixed metals together in certain proportions, followed by gradual cooling and annealing.
[src:ferrite-magnet/aluminum-p01] Bonding in them is predominantly metallic and the crystal structure primarily depends on efficiency of packing.
[src:ferrite-magnet/aluminum-p01] There are few compounds with lower oxidation states.
[src:ferrite-magnet/aluminum-p01] Some are aluminium(I) compounds: AlF, AlCl, AlBr, and AlI all exist in the gaseous phase when the respective trihalide is heated with aluminium, and at cryogenic temperatures.
[src:ferrite-magnet/aluminum-p01] A stable derivative of aluminium monoiodide is the cyclic adduct formed with triethylamine, Al4I4(NEt3)4.
[src:ferrite-magnet/aluminum-p01] Al2O and Al2S also exist but are very unstable.
[src:ferrite-magnet/aluminum-p01] Very simple aluminium(II) compounds are invoked or observed in the reactions of Al metal with oxidants.
[src:ferrite-magnet/aluminum-p01] For example, aluminium monoxide, AlO, has been detected in the gas phase after explosion and in stellar absorption spectra.
[src:ferrite-magnet/aluminum-p01] More thoroughly investigated are compounds of the formula R4Al2 which contain an Al–Al bond and where R is a large organic ligand.
[src:ferrite-magnet/aluminum-p01] A variety of compounds of empirical formula AlR3 and AlR1.5Cl1.5 exist.
[src:ferrite-magnet/aluminum-p01] The aluminium trialkyls and triaryls are either reactive, volatile, and colorless liquids or low-melting solids.
[src:ferrite-magnet/aluminum-p01] They catch fire spontaneously in air and react with water, thus necessitating precautions when handling them.
[src:ferrite-magnet/aluminum-p01] They often form dimers, unlike their boron analogues, but this tendency diminishes for branched-chain alkyls (e.g.
[src:ferrite-magnet/aluminum-p01] For example, triisobutylaluminium exists as an equilibrium mixture of the monomer and dimer.
[src:ferrite-magnet/aluminum-p01] These dimers, such as trimethylaluminium (Al2Me6), usually feature tetrahedral Al centers formed by dimerization with some alkyl group bridging between both aluminium atoms.
[src:ferrite-magnet/aluminum-p01] They are hard acids and react readily with ligands, forming adducts.
[src:ferrite-magnet/aluminum-p01] In industry, they are mostly used in alkene insertion reactions, as discovered by Karl Ziegler, most importantly in "growth reactions" that form long-chain unbranched primary alkenes and alcohols, and in the low-pressure polymerization of ethene and propene.
[src:ferrite-magnet/aluminum-p01] There are also some heterocyclic and cluster organoaluminium compounds involving Al–N bonds.
[src:ferrite-magnet/aluminum-p01] The industrially most important aluminium hydride is lithium aluminium hydride (LiAlH4), which is used as a reducing agent in organic chemistry.
[src:ferrite-magnet/aluminum-p01] It can be produced from lithium hydride and aluminium trichloride.
[src:ferrite-magnet/aluminum-p01] The simplest hydride, aluminium hydride or alane, is not as important.
[src:ferrite-magnet/aluminum-p01] It is a polymer with the formula (AlH3)*n*, which is in contrast to the corresponding boron hydride that is a dimer with the formula (BH3)2.
[src:ferrite-magnet/aluminum-p01] Aluminium's per-particle abundance in the Solar System is 3.15 ppm (parts per million).
[src:ferrite-magnet/aluminum-p01] It is the twelfth most abundant of all elements and third most abundant among the elements that have odd atomic numbers, after hydrogen and nitrogen.
[src:ferrite-magnet/aluminum-p01] The only stable isotope of aluminium, 27Al, is the eighteenth most abundant nucleus in the universe.
[src:ferrite-magnet/aluminum-p01] It is created almost entirely after fusion of carbon in massive stars that will later become Type II supernovas: this fusion creates 26Mg, which upon capturing free protons and neutrons, becomes aluminium.
[src:ferrite-magnet/aluminum-p01] Some smaller quantities of 27Al are created in hydrogen burning shells of evolved stars, where 26Mg can capture free protons.
[src:ferrite-magnet/aluminum-p01] Essentially all aluminium now in existence is 27Al.
[src:ferrite-magnet/aluminum-p01] 26Al was present in the early Solar System with abundance of 0.005% relative to 27Al but its half-life of 728,000 years is too short for any original nuclei to survive; 26Al is therefore extinct.
[src:ferrite-magnet/aluminum-p01] Unlike for 27Al, hydrogen burning is the primary source of 26Al, with the nuclide emerging after a nucleus of 25Mg catches a free proton.
[src:ferrite-magnet/aluminum-p01] However, the trace quantities of 26Al that do exist are the most common gamma ray emitter in the interstellar gas; if the original 26Al were still present, gamma ray maps of the Milky Way would be brighter.
[src:ferrite-magnet/aluminum-p01] Overall, the Earth is about 1.59% aluminium by mass (seventh in abundance by mass).
[src:ferrite-magnet/aluminum-p01] Aluminium occurs in greater proportion in the Earth's crust than in the universe at large.
[src:ferrite-magnet/aluminum-p01] This is because aluminium easily forms the oxide and becomes bound into rocks and stays in the Earth's crust, while less reactive metals sink to the core.
[src:ferrite-magnet/aluminum-p01] In the Earth's crust, aluminium is the most abundant metallic element (8.23% by mass) and the third most abundant of all elements (after oxygen and silicon).
[src:ferrite-magnet/aluminum-p01] A large number of silicates in the Earth's crust contain aluminium.
[src:ferrite-magnet/aluminum-p01] In contrast, the Earth's mantle is only 2.38% aluminium by mass.
[src:ferrite-magnet/aluminum-p01] Aluminium also occurs in seawater at a concentration of 0.41 μg/kg.
[src:ferrite-magnet/aluminum-p01] Because of its strong affinity for oxygen, aluminium is almost never found in the elemental state; instead it is found in oxides or silicates.
[src:ferrite-magnet/aluminum-p01] Feldspars, the most common group of minerals in the Earth's crust, are aluminosilicates.
[src:ferrite-magnet/aluminum-p01] Aluminium also occurs in the minerals beryl, cryolite, garnet, spinel, and turquoise.
[src:ferrite-magnet/aluminum-p01] Impurities in alumina yield gemstones: for example, chromium yields ruby and iron yields sapphire.
[src:ferrite-magnet/aluminum-p01] Native aluminium metal is extremely rare and can only be found as a minor phase in low oxygen fugacity environments, such as the interiors of certain volcanoes.
[src:ferrite-magnet/aluminum-p01] Native aluminium has been reported in cold seeps in the northeastern continental slope of the South China Sea.
[src:ferrite-magnet/aluminum-p01] It is possible that these deposits resulted from bacterial reduction of tetrahydroxoaluminate Al(OH)4−.
[src:ferrite-magnet/aluminum-p01] Although aluminium is a common and widespread element, not all aluminium minerals are economically viable sources of the metal.
[src:ferrite-magnet/aluminum-p01] Almost all metallic aluminium is produced from the ore bauxite (AlO*x*(OH)3–2*x*).
[src:ferrite-magnet/aluminum-p01] Bauxite occurs as a weathering product of low iron and silica bedrock in tropical climatic conditions.
[src:ferrite-magnet/aluminum-p01] In 2017, most bauxite was mined in Australia, China, Guinea, and India.
[src:ferrite-magnet/aluminum-p01] The history of aluminium has been shaped by usage of alum.
[src:ferrite-magnet/aluminum-p01] The first written record of alum, made by Greek historian Herodotus, dates back to the 5th century BCE.
[src:ferrite-magnet/aluminum-p01] The ancients are known to have used alum as a dyeing mordant and for city defense as a fire-resistant coating for wood.
[src:ferrite-magnet/aluminum-p01] After the Crusades, alum, an indispensable good in the European fabric industry, was a subject of international commerce; it was imported to Europe from the eastern Mediterranean until the mid-15th century.
[src:ferrite-magnet/aluminum-p01] The nature of alum remained unknown until Swiss physician Paracelsus suggested alum was a salt of an earth of alum around 1530.
[src:ferrite-magnet/aluminum-p01] German doctor and chemist Andreas Libavius experimentally confirmed this in 1595.
[src:ferrite-magnet/aluminum-p01] German chemist Friedrich Hoffmann announced his belief that the base of alum was a distinct earth in 1722.
[src:ferrite-magnet/aluminum-p01] German chemist Andreas Sigismund Marggraf synthesized alumina in 1754 by boiling clay in sulfuric acid and subsequently adding potash.
[src:ferrite-magnet/aluminum-p01] Attempts to produce aluminium date back to 1760.
[src:ferrite-magnet/aluminum-p01] The first successful attempt, however, was completed in 1824 by Danish physicist and chemist Hans Christian Ørsted.
[src:ferrite-magnet/aluminum-p01] He reacted anhydrous aluminium chloride with potassium amalgam, yielding a lump of metal looking similar to tin.
[src:ferrite-magnet/aluminum-p01] He presented his results and demonstrated a sample of the new metal in 1825.
[src:ferrite-magnet/aluminum-p01] In 1827, German chemist Friedrich Wöhler repeated Ørsted's experiments but did not identify any aluminium.
[src:ferrite-magnet/aluminum-p01] (The reason for this inconsistency was only discovered in 1921.) He conducted a similar experiment in the same year by mixing anhydrous aluminium chloride with potassium (the Wöhler process) and produced a powder of aluminium.
[src:ferrite-magnet/aluminum-p01] In 1845, he was able to produce small pieces of the metal and described some physical properties of this metal.
[src:ferrite-magnet/aluminum-p01] For many years thereafter, Wöhler was credited as the discoverer of aluminium.
[src:ferrite-magnet/aluminum-p01] As Wöhler's method could not yield great quantities of aluminium, the metal remained rare; its cost exceeded that of gold.
[src:ferrite-magnet/aluminum-p01] The first industrial production of aluminium was established in 1856 by French chemist Henri Étienne Sainte-Claire Deville and companions.
[src:ferrite-magnet/aluminum-p01] Sainte-Claire Deville had discovered that aluminium trichloride could be reduced by sodium, which was more convenient and less expensive than potassium, which Wöhler had used.
[src:ferrite-magnet/aluminum-p01] Even then, aluminium was still not of great purity and produced aluminium differed in properties by sample.
[src:ferrite-magnet/aluminum-p01] Because of its electricity-conducting capacity, aluminium was used as the cap of the Washington Monument, completed in 1885, the tallest building in the world at the time.
[src:ferrite-magnet/aluminum-p01] The non-corroding metal cap was intended to serve as a lightning rod peak.
[src:ferrite-magnet/aluminum-p01] The first industrial large-scale production method was independently developed in 1886 by French engineer Paul Héroult and American engineer Charles Martin Hall; it is now known as the Hall–Héroult process.
[src:ferrite-magnet/aluminum-p01] The Hall–Héroult process converts alumina into metal.
[src:ferrite-magnet/aluminum-p01] Austrian chemist Carl Joseph Bayer discovered a way of purifying bauxite to yield alumina, now known as the Bayer process, in 1889.
[src:ferrite-magnet/aluminum-p01] Modern production of aluminium is based on the Bayer and Hall–Héroult processes.
[src:ferrite-magnet/aluminum-p01] As large-scale production caused aluminium prices to drop, the metal became widely used in jewelry, eyeglass frames, optical instruments, tableware, and foil, and other everyday items in the 1890s and early 20th century.
[src:ferrite-magnet/aluminum-p01] Aluminium's ability to form hard yet light alloys with other metals provided the metal with many uses at the time.
[src:ferrite-magnet/aluminum-p01] During World War I, major governments demanded large shipments of aluminium for light strong airframes; during World War II, demand by major governments for aviation was even higher.
[src:ferrite-magnet/aluminum-p01] From the early 20th century to 1980, the aluminium industry was characterized by cartelization, as aluminium firms colluded to keep prices high and stable.
[src:ferrite-magnet/aluminum-p01] The first aluminium cartel, the Aluminium Association, was founded in 1901 by the Pittsburgh Reduction Company (renamed Alcoa in 1907) and Aluminium Industrie AG.
[src:ferrite-magnet/aluminum-p01] The British Aluminium Company, Produits Chimiques d'Alais et de la Camargue, and Société Électro-Métallurgique de Froges also joined the cartel.
[src:ferrite-magnet/aluminum-p01] By the mid-20th century, aluminium had become a part of everyday life and an essential component of housewares.
[src:ferrite-magnet/aluminum-p01] In 1954, production of aluminium surpassed that of copper, historically second in production only to iron, making it the most produced non-ferrous metal.
[src:ferrite-magnet/aluminum-p01] During the mid-20th century, aluminium emerged as a civil engineering material, with building applications in both basic construction and interior finish work, and increasingly being used in military engineering, for both airplanes and armored vehicle engines.
[src:ferrite-magnet/aluminum-p01] Earth's first artificial satellite, launched in 1957, consisted of two separate aluminium semi-spheres joined and all subsequent space vehicles have used aluminium to some extent.
[src:ferrite-magnet/aluminum-p01] The aluminium can was invented in 1956 and employed as a storage for drinks in 1958.
[src:ferrite-magnet/aluminum-p01] Throughout the 20th century, the production of aluminium rose rapidly: while the world production of aluminium in 1900 was 6,800 metric tons, the annual production first exceeded 100,000 metric tons in 1916; 1,000,000 tons in 1941; 10,000,000 tons in 1971.
[src:ferrite-magnet/aluminum-p01] In the 1970s, the increased demand for aluminium made it an exchange commodity; it entered the London Metal Exchange, the oldest industrial metal exchange in the world, in 1978.
[src:ferrite-magnet/aluminum-p01] The output continued to grow: the annual production of aluminium exceeded 50,000,000 metric tons in 2013.
[src:ferrite-magnet/aluminum-p01] The real price for aluminium declined from $14,000 per metric ton in 1900 to $2,340 in 1948 (in 1998 United States dollars).
[src:ferrite-magnet/aluminum-p01] Extraction and processing costs were lowered over technological progress and the scale of the economies.
[src:ferrite-magnet/aluminum-p01] However, the need to exploit lower-grade poorer quality deposits and the use of fast increasing input costs (above all, energy) increased the net cost of aluminium; the real price began to grow in the 1970s with the rise of energy cost.
[src:ferrite-magnet/aluminum-p01] Production moved from the industrialized countries to countries where production was cheaper.
[src:ferrite-magnet/aluminum-p01] Production costs in the late 20th century changed because of advances in technology, lower energy prices, exchange rates of the United States dollar, and alumina prices.
[src:ferrite-magnet/aluminum-p01] The BRIC countries' combined share in primary production and primary consumption grew substantially in the first decade of the 21st century.
[src:ferrite-magnet/aluminum-p01] China is accumulating an especially large share of the world's production thanks to an abundance of resources, cheap energy, and governmental stimuli; it also increased its consumption share from 2% in 1972 to 40% in 2010.
[src:ferrite-magnet/aluminum-p01] In the United States, Western Europe, and Japan, most aluminium was consumed in transportation, engineering, construction, and packaging.
[src:ferrite-magnet/aluminum-p01] In 2021, prices for industrial metals such as aluminium have soared to near-record levels as energy shortages in China drive up costs for electricity.
[src:ferrite-magnet/aluminum-p01] The names *aluminium* and *aluminum* are derived from the word *alumine*, an obsolete term for *alumina*, the primary naturally occurring oxide of aluminium.
[src:ferrite-magnet/aluminum-p01] *Alumine* was borrowed from French, which in turn derived it from *alumen*, the classical Latin name for alum, the mineral from which it was collected.
[src:ferrite-magnet/aluminum-p01] The Latin word *alumen* stems from the Proto-Indo-European root **alu-* meaning "bitter" or "beer".
[src:ferrite-magnet/aluminum-p01] The English name *alum* does not come directly from Latin, whereas *alumine*/*alumina* comes from the Latin word *alumen* (on declension, *alumen* changes to *alumin-*).
[src:ferrite-magnet/aluminum-p01] British chemist Humphry Davy, who performed a number of experiments aimed to isolate the metal, is credited as the person who named the element.
[src:ferrite-magnet/aluminum-p01] The first name proposed for the metal to be isolated from alum was *alumium*, which Davy suggested in an 1808 article on his electrochemical research, published in Philosophical Transactions of the Royal Society.
[src:ferrite-magnet/aluminum-p01] It appeared that the name was created from the English word *alum* and the Latin suffix *-ium*; but it was customary then to give elements names originating in Latin, so this name was not adopted universally.
[src:ferrite-magnet/aluminum-p01] The name *alumium* was criticized by contemporary chemists from France, Germany, and Sweden, who insisted the metal should be named for the oxide, alumina, from which it would be isolated.
[src:ferrite-magnet/aluminum-p01] One example was *Essai sur la Nomenclature chimique* (July 1811), written in French by a Swedish chemist, Jöns Jacob Berzelius, in which the name *aluminium* is given to the element that would be synthesized from alum.
[src:ferrite-magnet/aluminum-p01] (Another article in the same journal issue also refers to the metal whose oxide is the basis of sapphire, i.e., the same metal, as to *aluminium*.) A January 1811 summary of one of Davy's lectures at the Royal Society mentioned the name *aluminium* as a possibility.
[src:ferrite-magnet/aluminum-p01] In 1812, Davy published his chemistry text *Elements of Chemical Philosophy* in which he used the spelling *aluminum*.
[src:ferrite-magnet/aluminum-p01] In 1812, British scientist Thomas Young wrote an anonymous review of Davy's book, in which he proposed the name *aluminium* instead of *aluminum*, which he thought had a "less classical sound".
[src:ferrite-magnet/aluminum-p01] This name persisted: although the *-um* spelling was occasionally used in Britain, the American scientific language used *-ium* from the start.
[src:ferrite-magnet/aluminum-p01] The French have used the spelling *aluminium* from the start.
[src:ferrite-magnet/aluminum-p01] Most scientists throughout the world used *-ium* in the 19th century; and it was entrenched in several other European languages, such as French, German, and Dutch.
[src:ferrite-magnet/aluminum-p01] In 1828, an American lexicographer, Noah Webster, entered only the *aluminum* spelling in his *American Dictionary of the English Language*.
[src:ferrite-magnet/aluminum-p01] In the 1830s, the *-um* spelling gained usage in the United States; by the 1860s, it had become the more common spelling there outside science.
[src:ferrite-magnet/aluminum-p01] In 1892, Hall used the *-um* spelling in his advertising handbill for his new electrolytic method of producing the metal, despite his constant use of the *-ium* spelling in all the patents he filed between 1886 and 1903.
[src:ferrite-magnet/aluminum-p01] It is unknown whether this spelling was introduced by mistake or intentionally, but Hall preferred *aluminum* since its introduction because it resembled *platinum*, the name of a prestigious metal.
[src:ferrite-magnet/aluminum-p01] By 1890, both spellings had been common in the United States, the *-ium* spelling being slightly more common; by 1895, the situation had reversed; by 1900, *aluminum* had become twice as common as *aluminium*; in the next decade, the *-um* spelling dominated American usage.
[src:ferrite-magnet/aluminum-p01] In 1925, the American Chemical Society adopted the spelling *aluminum*.
[src:ferrite-magnet/aluminum-p01] The International Union of Pure and Applied Chemistry (IUPAC) adopted *aluminium* as the standard international name for the element in 1990.
[src:ferrite-magnet/aluminum-p01] In 1993, they recognized *aluminum* as an acceptable variant; the most recent 2005 edition of the IUPAC nomenclature of inorganic chemistry also acknowledges this spelling.
[src:ferrite-magnet/aluminum-p01] IUPAC official publications use the *-ium* spelling as primary, and they list both where it is appropriate.
[src:ferrite-magnet/aluminum-p01] Their usage is currently regional: *aluminum* dominates in the United States and Canada; *aluminium* is prevalent in the rest of the English-speaking world.
[src:ferrite-magnet/aluminum-p01] German physicist Ludwig Wilhelm Gilbert had proposed *Thonerde-metall*, after the German *Thonerde* for alumina, in his *Annalen der Physik* but that name never caught on at all even in Germany.
[src:ferrite-magnet/aluminum-p01] Richards in 1891 found just one occurrence of *argillium* in Swedish, from the French *argille* for clay.
[src:ferrite-magnet/aluminum-p01] The production of aluminium starts with the extraction of bauxite rock from the ground.
[src:ferrite-magnet/aluminum-p01] The bauxite is processed and transformed using the Bayer process into alumina, which is then processed using the Hall–Héroult process, resulting in the final aluminium.
[src:ferrite-magnet/aluminum-p01] Aluminium production is highly energy-consuming, and so the producers tend to locate smelters in places where electric power is both plentiful and inexpensive.
[src:ferrite-magnet/aluminum-p01] Production of one kilogram of aluminium requires 7 kilograms of oil energy equivalent, as compared to 1.5 kilograms for steel and 2 kilograms for plastic.
[src:ferrite-magnet/aluminum-p01] As of 2024, the world's largest producers of aluminium were China, India, Russia, Canada, and the United Arab Emirates, while China is by far the top producer of aluminium with a world share of over 55%.
[src:ferrite-magnet/aluminum-p01] According to the International Resource Panel's Metal Stocks in Society report, the global per capita stock of aluminium in use in society (i.e. in cars, buildings, electronics, etc.) is 80 kg (180 lb).
[src:ferrite-magnet/aluminum-p01] Much of this is in more-developed countries (350–500 kg (770–1,100 lb) per capita) rather than less-developed countries (35 kg (77 lb) per capita).
[src:ferrite-magnet/aluminum-p01] Bauxite is converted to alumina by the Bayer process.
[src:ferrite-magnet/aluminum-p01] Bauxite is blended for uniform composition and then is ground fine.
[src:ferrite-magnet/aluminum-p01] After this reaction, the slurry is at a temperature above its atmospheric boiling point.
[src:ferrite-magnet/aluminum-p01] It is cooled by removing steam as pressure is reduced.
[src:ferrite-magnet/aluminum-p01] The bauxite residue is separated from the solution and discarded.
[src:ferrite-magnet/aluminum-p01] The solution, free of solids, is seeded with small crystals of aluminium hydroxide; this causes decomposition of the [Al(OH)4]− ions to aluminium hydroxide.
[src:ferrite-magnet/aluminum-p01] After about half of aluminium has precipitated, the mixture is sent to classifiers.
[src:ferrite-magnet/aluminum-p01] Small crystals of aluminium hydroxide are collected to serve as seeding agents; coarse particles are converted to alumina by heating; the excess solution is removed by evaporation, (if needed) purified, and recycled.
[src:ferrite-magnet/aluminum-p01] The conversion of alumina to aluminium is achieved by the Hall–Héroult process.
[src:ferrite-magnet/aluminum-p01] In this energy-intensive process, a solution of alumina in a molten (940 and 970 °C (1,720 and 1,780 °F)) mixture of cryolite (Na3AlF6) with calcium fluoride is electrolyzed to produce metallic aluminium.
[src:ferrite-magnet/aluminum-p01] The liquid aluminium sinks to the bottom of the solution and is tapped off, and usually cast into large blocks called aluminium billets for further processing.
[src:ferrite-magnet/aluminum-p01] Anodes of the electrolysis cell are made of carbon—the most resistant material against fluoride corrosion—and either bake at the process or are prebaked.
[src:ferrite-magnet/aluminum-p01] The former, also called Söderberg anodes, are less power-efficient and fumes released during baking are costly to collect, which is why they are being replaced by prebaked anodes even though they save the power, energy, and labor to prebake the cathodes.
[src:ferrite-magnet/aluminum-p01] Carbon for anodes should be preferably pure so that neither aluminium nor the electrolyte is contaminated with ash.
[src:ferrite-magnet/aluminum-p01] Despite carbon's resistivity against corrosion, it is still consumed at a rate of 0.4–0.5 kg per each kilogram of produced aluminium.
[src:ferrite-magnet/aluminum-p01] Cathodes are made of anthracite; high purity for them is not required because impurities leach only very slowly.
[src:ferrite-magnet/aluminum-p01] The cathode is consumed at a rate of 0.02–0.04 kg per each kilogram of produced aluminium.
[src:ferrite-magnet/aluminum-p01] A cell is usually terminated after 2–6 years following a failure of the cathode.
[src:ferrite-magnet/aluminum-p01] The Hall–Heroult process produces aluminium with a purity of above 99%.
[src:ferrite-magnet/aluminum-p01] Further purification can be done by the Hoopes process.
[src:ferrite-magnet/aluminum-p01] This process involves the electrolysis of molten aluminium with a sodium, barium, and aluminium fluoride electrolyte.
[src:ferrite-magnet/aluminum-p01] The resulting aluminium has a purity of 99.99%.
[src:ferrite-magnet/aluminum-p01] Electric power represents about 20 to 40% of the cost of producing aluminium, depending on the location of the smelter.
[src:ferrite-magnet/aluminum-p01] Aluminium production consumes roughly 5% of electricity generated in the United States.
[src:ferrite-magnet/aluminum-p01] Because of this, alternatives to the Hall–Héroult process have been researched, but none has turned out to be economically feasible.
[src:ferrite-magnet/aluminum-p01] Recovery of the metal through recycling has become an important task of the aluminium industry.
[src:ferrite-magnet/aluminum-p01] Recycling was a low-profile activity until the late 1960s, when the growing use of aluminium beverage cans brought it to public awareness.
[src:ferrite-magnet/aluminum-p01] Recycling involves melting the scrap, a process that requires only 5% of the energy used to produce aluminium from ore, though a significant part (up to 15% of the input material) is lost as dross (ash-like oxide).
[src:ferrite-magnet/aluminum-p01] An aluminium stack melter produces significantly less dross, with values reported below 1%.
[src:ferrite-magnet/aluminum-p01] White dross from primary aluminium production and from secondary recycling operations still contains useful quantities of aluminium that can be extracted industrially.
[src:ferrite-magnet/aluminum-p01] The process produces aluminium billets, together with a highly complex waste material.
[src:ferrite-magnet/aluminum-p01] It reacts with water, releasing a mixture of gases including, among others, acetylene, hydrogen sulfide and significant amounts of ammonia.
[src:ferrite-magnet/aluminum-p01] Despite these difficulties, the waste is used as a filler in asphalt and concrete.
[src:ferrite-magnet/aluminum-p01] Its potential for hydrogen production has also been considered and researched.
[src:ferrite-magnet/aluminum-p01] The global production of aluminium in 2016 was 58.8 million metric tons.
[src:ferrite-magnet/aluminum-p01] It exceeded that of any other metal except iron (1,231 million metric tons).
[src:ferrite-magnet/aluminum-p01] Aluminium is almost always alloyed, which markedly improves its mechanical properties, especially when tempered.
[src:ferrite-magnet/aluminum-p01] For example, the common aluminium foils and beverage cans are alloys of 92% to 99% aluminium.
[src:ferrite-magnet/aluminum-p01] The main alloying agents for both wrought and cast aluminium are copper, zinc, magnesium, manganese, and silicon (e.g., duralumin) with the levels of other metals in a few percent by weight.
[src:ferrite-magnet/aluminum-p01] Aluminium is the main substitute to copper and its applications to the traditional domains of copper have seen increased interest when copper prices are high such as in 2011–2014 and 2021.
[src:ferrite-magnet/aluminum-p01] There is a competition in the use of aluminium and copper in the automotive industry, but in other uses such as in the construction industry and in underground and submarine cables aluminium has been largely unable to compete with copper.
[src:ferrite-magnet/aluminum-p01] The great majority (about 90%) of aluminium oxide is converted to metallic aluminium.
[src:ferrite-magnet/aluminum-p01] Being a very hard material (Mohs hardness 9), alumina is widely used as an abrasive; being extraordinarily chemically inert, it is useful in highly reactive environments such as high pressure sodium lamps.
[src:ferrite-magnet/aluminum-p01] Aluminium oxide is commonly used as a catalyst for industrial processes; e.g. the Claus process to convert hydrogen sulfide to sulfur in refineries and to alkylate amines.
[src:ferrite-magnet/aluminum-p01] Many industrial catalysts are supported by alumina, meaning that the expensive catalyst material is dispersed over a surface of the inert alumina.
[src:ferrite-magnet/aluminum-p01] Another principal use is as a drying agent or absorbent.
[src:ferrite-magnet/aluminum-p01] Several sulfates of aluminium have industrial and commercial application.
[src:ferrite-magnet/aluminum-p01] Aluminium sulfate (in its hydrate form) is produced on the annual scale of several millions of metric tons.
[src:ferrite-magnet/aluminum-p01] About two-thirds is consumed in water treatment.
[src:ferrite-magnet/aluminum-p01] The next major application is in the manufacture of paper.
[src:ferrite-magnet/aluminum-p01] It is also used as a mordant in dyeing, in pickling seeds, deodorizing of mineral oils, in leather tanning, and in production of other aluminium compounds.
[src:ferrite-magnet/aluminum-p01] Two kinds of alum, ammonium alum and potassium alum, were formerly used as mordants and in leather tanning, but their use has significantly declined following availability of high-purity aluminium sulfate.
[src:ferrite-magnet/aluminum-p01] Anhydrous aluminium chloride is used as a catalyst in chemical and petrochemical industries, the dyeing industry, and in synthesis of various inorganic and organic compounds.
[src:ferrite-magnet/aluminum-p01] Aluminium hydroxychlorides are used in purifying water, in the paper industry, and as antiperspirants.
[src:ferrite-magnet/aluminum-p01] Sodium aluminate is used in treating water and as an accelerator of solidification of cement.
[src:ferrite-magnet/aluminum-p02] Despite its widespread occurrence in the Earth's crust, aluminium has no known function in biology.
[src:ferrite-magnet/aluminum-p02] At pH 6–9 (relevant for most natural waters), aluminium precipitates out of water as the hydroxide and is hence not available; most elements behaving this way have no biological role or are toxic.
[src:ferrite-magnet/aluminum-p02] Aluminium sulfate has an LD50 of 6207 mg/kg (oral, mouse).
[src:ferrite-magnet/aluminum-p02] Aluminium is classified as a non-carcinogen by the United States Department of Health and Human Services.
[src:ferrite-magnet/aluminum-p02] A review published in 1988 said that there was little evidence that normal exposure to aluminium presents a risk to healthy adult, and a 2014 multi-element toxicology review was unable to find deleterious effects of aluminium consumed in amounts not greater than 40 mg/day per kg of body mass.
[src:ferrite-magnet/aluminum-p02] Most ingested aluminium is eliminated in feces, and much of what enters the bloodstream is excreted in urine; however, not all absorbed or parenterally administered aluminium is cleared through urinary excretion.
[src:ferrite-magnet/aluminum-p02] Aluminium, although rarely, can cause vitamin D-resistant osteomalacia, erythropoietin-resistant microcytic anemia, and central nervous system alterations.
[src:ferrite-magnet/aluminum-p02] People with kidney insufficiency are especially at a risk.
[src:ferrite-magnet/aluminum-p02] Chronic ingestion of hydrated aluminium silicates (for excess gastric acidity control) may result in aluminium binding to intestinal contents and increased elimination of other metals, such as iron or zinc; sufficiently high doses (>50 g/day) can cause anemia.
[src:ferrite-magnet/aluminum-p02] During the 1988 Camelford water pollution incident, people in Camelford had their drinking water contaminated with aluminium sulfate for several weeks.
[src:ferrite-magnet/aluminum-p02] A final report into the incident in 2013 concluded it was unlikely that this had caused long-term health problems.
[src:ferrite-magnet/aluminum-p02] Aluminium has been suspected of being a possible cause of Alzheimer's disease, but research into this for over 40 years has found, as of 2018, no good evidence of causal effect.
[src:ferrite-magnet/aluminum-p02] Aluminium increases estrogen-related gene expression in human breast cancer cells cultured in the laboratory.
[src:ferrite-magnet/aluminum-p02] In very high doses, aluminium is associated with altered function of the blood–brain barrier.
[src:ferrite-magnet/aluminum-p02] A small percentage of people have contact allergies to aluminium and experience itchy red rashes, headache, muscle pain, joint pain, poor memory, insomnia, depression, asthma, irritable bowel syndrome, or other symptoms upon contact with products containing aluminium.
[src:ferrite-magnet/aluminum-p02] Exposure to powdered aluminium or aluminium welding fumes can cause pulmonary fibrosis.
[src:ferrite-magnet/aluminum-p02] Fine aluminium powder can ignite or explode, posing another workplace hazard.
[src:ferrite-magnet/aluminum-p02] Drinking water contains more aluminium than solid food; however, aluminium in food may be absorbed more than aluminium from water.
[src:ferrite-magnet/aluminum-p02] Dietary exposure in Europeans averages to 0.2–1.5 mg/kg/week but can be as high as 2.3 mg/kg/week.
[src:ferrite-magnet/aluminum-p02] Higher exposure levels of aluminium are mostly limited to plumbers, masons, electrical workers, machinists, and surgeons.
[src:ferrite-magnet/aluminum-p02] Consumption of antacids, antiperspirants, vaccines, and cosmetics provide possible routes of exposure.
[src:ferrite-magnet/aluminum-p02] Consumption of acidic foods or liquids with aluminium enhances aluminium absorption, and maltol has been shown to increase the accumulation of aluminium in nerve and bone tissues.
[src:ferrite-magnet/aluminum-p02] In case of suspected sudden intake of a large amount of aluminium, the only treatment is deferoxamine mesylate which may be given to help eliminate aluminium from the body by chelation therapy.
[src:ferrite-magnet/aluminum-p02] However, this should be applied with caution as this reduces not only aluminium body levels, but also those of other metals such as copper or iron.
[src:ferrite-magnet/aluminum-p02] High levels of aluminium occur near mining sites; small amounts of aluminium are released to the environment at coal-fired power plants or incinerators.
[src:ferrite-magnet/aluminum-p02] Aluminium in the air is washed out by the rain or normally settles down but small particles of aluminium remain in the air for a long time.
[src:ferrite-magnet/aluminum-p02] Acidic precipitation is the main natural factor to mobilize aluminium from natural sources and the main reason for the environmental effects of aluminium; however, the main factor of presence of aluminium in salt and freshwater are the industrial processes that also release aluminium into air.
[src:ferrite-magnet/aluminum-p02] In water, aluminium acts as a toxic agent on gill-breathing animals such as fish when the water is acidic, in which aluminium may precipitate on gills, which causes loss of plasma- and hemolymph ions leading to osmoregulatory failure.
[src:ferrite-magnet/aluminum-p02] Organic complexes of aluminium may be easily absorbed and interfere with metabolism in mammals and birds, even though this rarely happens in practice.
[src:ferrite-magnet/aluminum-p02] Aluminium is primary among the factors that reduce plant growth on acidic soils.
[src:ferrite-magnet/aluminum-p02] Although it is generally harmless to plant growth in pH-neutral soils, in acid soils the concentration of toxic Al3+ cations increases and disturbs root growth and function.
[src:ferrite-magnet/aluminum-p02] Wheat has developed a tolerance to aluminium, releasing organic compounds that bind to harmful aluminium cations.
[src:ferrite-magnet/aluminum-p02] Sorghum is believed to have the same tolerance mechanism.
[src:ferrite-magnet/aluminum-p02] Aluminium production possesses its own challenges to the environment on each step of the production process.
[src:ferrite-magnet/aluminum-p02] The major challenge is the emission of greenhouse gases.
[src:ferrite-magnet/aluminum-p02] These gases result from electrical consumption of the smelters and the byproducts of processing.
[src:ferrite-magnet/aluminum-p02] The most potent of these gases are perfluorocarbons, namely CF4 and C2F6, from the smelting process.
[src:ferrite-magnet/aluminum-p02] Biodegradation of metallic aluminium is extremely rare; most aluminium-corroding organisms do not directly attack or consume the aluminium, but instead produce corrosive wastes.
[src:ferrite-magnet/aluminum-p02] The fungus *Geotrichum candidum* can consume the aluminium in compact discs.
[src:ferrite-magnet/aluminum-p02] The bacterium *Pseudomonas aeruginosa* and the fungus *Cladosporium resinae* are commonly detected in aircraft fuel tanks that use kerosene-based fuels (not avgas), and laboratory cultures can degrade aluminium.
[src:ferrite-magnet/american-institute-of-physics] The **American Institute of Physics** (**AIP**) promotes science and the profession of physics, publishes physics journals, and produces publications for scientific and engineering societies.
[src:ferrite-magnet/american-institute-of-physics] The AIP is made up of various member societies.
[src:ferrite-magnet/american-institute-of-physics] Its corporate headquarters are at the American Center for Physics in College Park, Maryland, but the institute also has offices in Melville, New York, and Beijing.
[src:ferrite-magnet/american-institute-of-physics] The AIP was founded in 1931 as a response to lack of funding for the sciences during the Great Depression.
[src:ferrite-magnet/american-institute-of-physics] The AIP was founded in 1931 at a joint meeting between four physics societies: the American Physical Society, the Optical Society of America, the Acoustical Society of America, and the Society of Rheology.
[src:ferrite-magnet/american-institute-of-physics] These were soon joined by the American Association of Physics Teachers, for a total of five societies.
[src:ferrite-magnet/american-institute-of-physics] It formally incorporated in 1932 consisting of five original "member societies", and a total of four thousand members.
[src:ferrite-magnet/american-institute-of-physics] As soon as the AIP was established it began publishing scientific journals.
[src:ferrite-magnet/american-institute-of-physics] By 1943, the AIP published eight journals: Physical Review, Reviews of Modern Physics, Journal of the Optical Society of America, Journal of the Acoustical Society of America, American Journal of Physics, Review of Scientific Instruments, Journal of Applied Physics, and Journal of Chemical Physics.
[src:ferrite-magnet/american-institute-of-physics] A new set of member societies was added beginning in the mid-1960s.
[src:ferrite-magnet/american-institute-of-physics] The organization restructured in 2013, creating a new subsidiary, *AIP Publishing LLC*, to manage physical publications of its journals with a smaller board.
[src:ferrite-magnet/american-institute-of-physics] The AIP has a subsidiary called *AIP Publishing* (wholly owned non-profit) dedicated to scholarly publishing by the AIP and its member societies, as well on behalf of other partners.
[src:ferrite-magnet/american-institute-of-physics] AIP created a manual of style first introduced in 1951, called AIP style, which also includes the AIP citation format.
[src:ferrite-magnet/american-institute-of-physics] It is the most commonly used style and citation format in physics publications.
[src:ferrite-magnet/anisotropy] Examples of anisotropy include light coming through a polarizer; another is wood, which is easier to split along its grain than across it because of the directional non-uniformity of the grain (the grain is the same in one direction, not all directions).
[src:ferrite-magnet/anisotropy] In the field of computer graphics, an anisotropic surface changes in appearance as it rotates about its geometric normal, as is the case with velvet.
[src:ferrite-magnet/anisotropy] Anisotropic filtering (AF) is a method of enhancing the image quality of textures on surfaces that are far away and viewed at a shallow angle.
[src:ferrite-magnet/anisotropy] Older techniques, such as bilinear and trilinear filtering, do not take into account the angle a surface is viewed from, which can result in aliasing or blurring of textures.
[src:ferrite-magnet/anisotropy] By reducing detail in one direction more than another, these effects can be reduced easily.
[src:ferrite-magnet/anisotropy] A chemical anisotropic filter is a membrane with increasingly smaller interstitial spaces in the direction of filtration so that the proximal regions filter out larger particles while distal regions progressively remove smaller particles.
[src:ferrite-magnet/anisotropy] This gradient structure prevents surface clogging, resulting in greater flow-through and more efficient filtration than uniform-pore filters.
[src:ferrite-magnet/anisotropy] In fluorescence spectroscopy, fluorescence anisotropy is calculated from the polarization properties of fluorescence emitted by samples excited with plane-polarized light.
[src:ferrite-magnet/anisotropy] When a fluorophore absorbs polarized light, it may rotate before re-emitting a photon, and anisotropy measurements reveal the average angular displacement that occurs between absorption and emission.
[src:ferrite-magnet/anisotropy] This makes fluorescence anisotropy a useful tool for determining the shape of a macromolecule or studying its local molecular mobility.
[src:ferrite-magnet/anisotropy] In NMR spectroscopy, the orientation of nuclei with respect to the applied magnetic field determines their chemical shift.
[src:ferrite-magnet/anisotropy] Anisotropic systems arise from molecules with regions of delocalized electron density, such as the π (pi) system of benzene, where circulating π electrons generate a diamagnetic ring current that produces a secondary magnetic field.
[src:ferrite-magnet/anisotropy] Depending on the spatial position of nearby nuclei, this secondary field either reinforces or opposes the applied field, causing the observed chemical shift to change, this is known as chemical shift anisotropy.
[src:ferrite-magnet/anisotropy] Images of a gravity-bound or man-made environment are particularly anisotropic in the orientation domain, with more image structure located at orientations parallel with or orthogonal to the direction of gravity (vertical and horizontal).
[src:ferrite-magnet/anisotropy] Physicists from University of California, Berkeley reported about their detection of the cosmic anisotropy in cosmic microwave background radiation in 1977.
[src:ferrite-magnet/anisotropy] Their experiment demonstrated the Doppler shift caused by the movement of the earth with respect to the early Universe matter, the source of the radiation.
[src:ferrite-magnet/anisotropy] Cosmic anisotropy has also been seen in the alignment of galaxies' rotation axes and polarization angles of quasars.
[src:ferrite-magnet/anisotropy] Physicists use the term anisotropy to describe direction-dependent properties of materials.
[src:ferrite-magnet/anisotropy] Magnetic anisotropy, for example, may occur in a plasma, so that its magnetic field is oriented in a preferred direction.
[src:ferrite-magnet/anisotropy] Plasmas may also show "filamentation" (such as that seen in lightning or a plasma globe) that is directional.
[src:ferrite-magnet/anisotropy] An *anisotropic liquid* has the fluidity of a normal liquid, but has an average structural order relative to each other along the molecular axis, unlike water or chloroform, which contain no structural ordering of the molecules.
[src:ferrite-magnet/anisotropy] Liquid crystals are examples of anisotropic liquids.
[src:ferrite-magnet/anisotropy] Some materials conduct heat in a way that is isotropic, that is independent of spatial orientation around the heat source.
[src:ferrite-magnet/anisotropy] Heat conduction is more commonly anisotropic, which implies that detailed geometric modeling of typically diverse materials being thermally managed is required.
[src:ferrite-magnet/anisotropy] The materials used to transfer and reject heat from the heat source in electronics are often anisotropic.
[src:ferrite-magnet/anisotropy] Many crystals are anisotropic to light ("optical anisotropy"), and exhibit properties such as birefringence.
[src:ferrite-magnet/anisotropy] Crystal optics describes light propagation in these media.
[src:ferrite-magnet/anisotropy] An "axis of anisotropy" is defined as the axis along which isotropy is broken (or an axis of symmetry, such as normal to crystalline layers).
[src:ferrite-magnet/anisotropy] Some materials can have multiple such optical axes.
[src:ferrite-magnet/anisotropy] Seismic anisotropy is the variation of seismic wavespeed with direction.
[src:ferrite-magnet/anisotropy] Seismic anisotropy is an indicator of long range order in a material, where features smaller than the seismic wavelength (e.g., crystals, cracks, pores, layers, or inclusions) have a dominant alignment.
[src:ferrite-magnet/anisotropy] This alignment leads to a directional variation of elasticity wavespeed.
[src:ferrite-magnet/anisotropy] Measuring the effects of anisotropy in seismic data can provide important information about processes and mineralogy in the Earth; significant seismic anisotropy has been detected in the Earth's crust, mantle, and inner core.
[src:ferrite-magnet/anisotropy] Geological formations with distinct layers of sedimentary material can exhibit electrical anisotropy; electrical conductivity in one direction (e.g. parallel to a layer), is different from that in another (e.g. perpendicular to a layer).
[src:ferrite-magnet/anisotropy] This property is used in the gas and oil exploration industry to identify hydrocarbon-bearing sands in sequences of sand and shale.
[src:ferrite-magnet/anisotropy] Sand-bearing hydrocarbon assets have high resistivity (low conductivity), whereas shales have lower resistivity.
[src:ferrite-magnet/anisotropy] Formation evaluation instruments measure this conductivity or resistivity, and the results are used to help find oil and gas in wells.
[src:ferrite-magnet/anisotropy] The mechanical anisotropy measured for some of the sedimentary rocks like coal and shale can change with corresponding changes in their surface properties like sorption when gases are produced from the coal and shale reservoirs.
[src:ferrite-magnet/anisotropy] The hydraulic conductivity of aquifers is often anisotropic for the same reason.
[src:ferrite-magnet/anisotropy] When calculating groundwater flow to drains or to wells, the difference between horizontal and vertical permeability must be taken into account; otherwise the results may be subject to error.
[src:ferrite-magnet/anisotropy] Most common rock-forming minerals are anisotropic, including quartz and feldspar.
[src:ferrite-magnet/anisotropy] Anisotropy in minerals is most reliably seen in their optical properties.
[src:ferrite-magnet/anisotropy] These optical properties form the basis of modern mineral identification methods, including those based on artificial intelligence technologies.
[src:ferrite-magnet/anisotropy] An example of an isotropic mineral is garnet.
[src:ferrite-magnet/anisotropy] Igneous rock like granite also shows the anisotropy due to the orientation of the minerals during the solidification process.
[src:ferrite-magnet/anisotropy] Anisotropy is also a well-known property in medical ultrasound imaging describing a different resulting echogenicity of soft tissues, such as tendons, when the angle of the transducer is changed.
[src:ferrite-magnet/anisotropy] Tendon fibers appear hyperechoic (bright) when the transducer is perpendicular to the tendon, but can appear hypoechoic (darker) when the transducer is angled obliquely.
[src:ferrite-magnet/anisotropy] This can be a source of interpretation error for inexperienced practitioners.
[src:ferrite-magnet/anisotropy] Anisotropy, in materials science, is a material's directional dependence of a physical property.
[src:ferrite-magnet/anisotropy] This is a critical consideration for materials selection in engineering applications.
[src:ferrite-magnet/anisotropy] A material with physical properties that are symmetric about an axis that is normal to a plane of isotropy is called a transversely isotropic material.
[src:ferrite-magnet/anisotropy] Tensor descriptions of material properties can be used to determine the directional dependence of that property.
[src:ferrite-magnet/anisotropy] For a monocrystalline material, anisotropy is associated with the crystal symmetry in the sense that more symmetric crystal types have fewer independent coefficients in the tensor description of a given property.
[src:ferrite-magnet/anisotropy] When a material is polycrystalline, the directional dependence on properties is often related to the processing techniques it has undergone.
[src:ferrite-magnet/anisotropy] A material with randomly oriented grains will be isotropic, whereas materials with texture will be often be anisotropic.
[src:ferrite-magnet/anisotropy] Textured materials are often the result of processing techniques like cold rolling, wire drawing, and heat treatment.
[src:ferrite-magnet/anisotropy] Mechanical properties of materials such as Young's modulus, ductility, yield strength, and high-temperature creep rate, are often dependent on the direction of measurement.
[src:ferrite-magnet/anisotropy] Fourth-rank tensor properties, like the elastic constants, are anisotropic, even for materials with cubic symmetry.
[src:ferrite-magnet/anisotropy] The Young's modulus relates stress and strain when an isotropic material is elastically deformed; to describe elasticity in an anisotropic material, stiffness (or compliance) tensors are used instead.
[src:ferrite-magnet/anisotropy] In metals, anisotropic elasticity behavior is present in all single crystals with three independent coefficients for cubic crystals, for example.
[src:ferrite-magnet/anisotropy] For face-centered cubic materials such as nickel and copper, the stiffness is highest along the <111> direction, normal to the close-packed planes, and smallest parallel to <100>.
[src:ferrite-magnet/anisotropy] Tungsten is so nearly isotropic at room temperature that it can be considered to have only two stiffness coefficients; aluminium is another metal that is nearly isotropic.
[src:ferrite-magnet/anisotropy] For an isotropic material, $G=E/[2(1+\nu )],$ where G is the shear modulus, E is the Young's modulus, and $\nu$ is the material's Poisson's ratio.
[src:ferrite-magnet/anisotropy] The latter expression is known as the Zener ratio, $a_{r}$ , where $C_{ij}$ refers to elastic constants in Voigt (vector-matrix) notation.
[src:ferrite-magnet/anisotropy] For an isotropic material, the ratio is one.
[src:ferrite-magnet/anisotropy] Limitation of the Zener ratio to cubic materials is waived in the Tensorial anisotropy index AT that takes into consideration all the 27 components of the fully anisotropic stiffness tensor.
[src:ferrite-magnet/anisotropy] The second component of this index $A^{A}$ covers the influence of stiffness coefficients that are nonzero only for non-cubic materials and remains zero otherwise.
[src:ferrite-magnet/anisotropy] Fiber-reinforced or layered composite materials exhibit anisotropic mechanical properties, due to orientation of the reinforcement material.
[src:ferrite-magnet/anisotropy] In many fiber-reinforced composites like carbon fiber or glass fiber based composites, the weave of the material (e.g. unidirectional or plain weave) can determine the extent of the anisotropy of the bulk material.
[src:ferrite-magnet/anisotropy] The tunability of orientation of the fibers allows for application-based designs of composite materials, depending on the direction of stresses applied onto the material.
[src:ferrite-magnet/anisotropy] Amorphous materials such as glass and polymers are typically isotropic.
[src:ferrite-magnet/anisotropy] Due to the highly randomized orientation of macromolecules in polymeric materials, polymers are in general described as isotropic.
[src:ferrite-magnet/anisotropy] However, mechanically gradient polymers can be engineered to have directionally dependent properties through processing techniques or introduction of anisotropy-inducing elements.
[src:ferrite-magnet/anisotropy] Researchers have built composite materials with aligned fibers and voids to generate anisotropic hydrogels, in order to mimic hierarchically ordered biological soft matter.
[src:ferrite-magnet/anisotropy] 3D printing, especially Fused Deposition Modeling, can introduce anisotropy into printed parts.
[src:ferrite-magnet/anisotropy] This is because FDM is designed to extrude and print layers of thermoplastic materials.
[src:ferrite-magnet/anisotropy] This creates materials that are strong when tensile stress is applied in parallel to the layers and weak when the material is perpendicular to the layers.
[src:ferrite-magnet/anisotropy] Anisotropic etching techniques (such as deep reactive-ion etching) are used in microfabrication processes to create well defined microscopic features with a high aspect ratio.
[src:ferrite-magnet/anisotropy] These features are commonly used in MEMS (microelectromechanical systems) and microfluidic devices, where the anisotropy of the features is needed to impart desired optical, electrical, or physical properties to the device.
[src:ferrite-magnet/anisotropy] Diffusion tensor imaging is an MRI technique that involves measuring the fractional anisotropy of the random motion (Brownian motion) of water molecules in the brain.
[src:ferrite-magnet/anisotropy] This difference in fractional anisotropy is exploited to create a map of the fiber tracts in the brains of the individual.
[src:ferrite-magnet/anisotropy] Radiance fields (see Bidirectional reflectance distribution function (BRDF)) from a reflective surface are often not isotropic in nature.
[src:ferrite-magnet/anisotropy] This makes calculations of the total energy being reflected from any scene a difficult quantity to calculate.
[src:ferrite-magnet/anisotropy] In remote sensing applications, anisotropy functions can be derived for specific scenes, immensely simplifying the calculation of the net reflectance or (thereby) the net irradiance of a scene.
[src:ferrite-magnet/anisotropy] For example, let the BRDF be $\gamma (\Omega _{i},\Omega _{v})$ where 'i' denotes incident direction and 'v' denotes viewing direction (as if from a satellite or other instrument).
[src:ferrite-magnet/anisotropy] It is of interest because, with knowledge of the anisotropy function as defined, a measurement of the BRDF from a single viewing direction (say, $\Omega _{v}$ ) yields a measure of the total scene reflectance (planar albedo) for that specific incident geometry (say, $\Omega _{i}$ ).
[src:ferrite-magnet/antenna-radio-p01] In radio-frequency engineering, an **antenna** (American English) or **aerial** (British English) is a structure used to convert alternating electric currents into radio waves for transmission, and to convert radio waves back into electric currents for reception.
[src:ferrite-magnet/antenna-radio-p01] It is the interface between radio waves propagating through space and electric currents moving in metal conductors, used with a transmitter or receiver.
[src:ferrite-magnet/antenna-radio-p01] In transmission, a radio transmitter supplies an electric current to the antenna's terminals, and the antenna radiates the energy from the current as electromagnetic waves (radio waves).
[src:ferrite-magnet/antenna-radio-p01] In reception, an antenna intercepts some of the power of a radio wave in order to produce an electric current at its terminals, that is applied to a receiver to be amplified.
[src:ferrite-magnet/antenna-radio-p01] Antennas are essential components of all radio equipment.
[src:ferrite-magnet/antenna-radio-p01] An antenna is an array of conductor segments (elements), electrically connected to the receiver or transmitter.
[src:ferrite-magnet/antenna-radio-p01] Antennas can be designed to transmit and receive radio waves in all horizontal directions equally (omnidirectional antennas), or preferentially in a particular direction (directional, or high-gain, or "beam" antennas).
[src:ferrite-magnet/antenna-radio-p01] An antenna may include components not connected to the transmitter, parabolic reflectors, horns, or parasitic elements, which serve to direct the radio waves into a beam or other desired radiation pattern.
[src:ferrite-magnet/antenna-radio-p01] Strong directivity and good transmitting efficiency when transmitting are hard to achieve with antennas whose dimensions are much smaller than a half wavelength.
[src:ferrite-magnet/antenna-radio-p01] The first antennas were built in 1886 by German physicist Heinrich Hertz in his pioneering experiments to prove the existence of electromagnetic waves predicted by the 1867 electromagnetic theory of James Clerk Maxwell.
[src:ferrite-magnet/antenna-radio-p01] Hertz placed dipole antennas at the focal point of parabolic reflectors for both transmitting and receiving.
[src:ferrite-magnet/antenna-radio-p01] Starting in 1895, Guglielmo Marconi began development of antennas practical for long-distance wireless telegraphy and opened a factory in Chelmsford, England, to manufacture his invention in 1898.
[src:ferrite-magnet/antenna-radio-p01] antenna receiving a radio wave: The electric field (E) of the wave excites oscillating currents (black arrows) in the receiver.
[src:ferrite-magnet/antenna-radio-p01] Antenna radiating radio waves: The transmitter applies an alternating current (red arrows) to the rods, which charges them alternately positive and negative, emitting loops of electric field.
[src:ferrite-magnet/antenna-radio-p01] The arrows of the loops get reversed each time the current changes polarity.
[src:ferrite-magnet/antenna-radio-p01] The words *antenna* and *aerial* are used interchangeably.
[src:ferrite-magnet/antenna-radio-p01] Occasionally the equivalent term "aerial" is used to specifically mean an elevated horizontal wire antenna.
[src:ferrite-magnet/antenna-radio-p01] The origin of the word *antenna* relative to wireless apparatus is attributed to Italian radio pioneer Guglielmo Marconi.
[src:ferrite-magnet/antenna-radio-p01] In the summer of 1895, Marconi began testing his wireless system outdoors on his father's estate near Bologna and soon began to experiment with long wire "aerials" suspended from a pole.
[src:ferrite-magnet/antenna-radio-p01] In Italian a tent pole is known as *l'antenna centrale*, and the pole with the wire was simply called *l'antenna*.
[src:ferrite-magnet/antenna-radio-p01] Until then wireless radiating transmitting and receiving elements were known simply as "terminals".
[src:ferrite-magnet/antenna-radio-p01] Because of his prominence, Marconi's use of the word *antenna* spread among wireless researchers and enthusiasts, and later to the general public.
[src:ferrite-magnet/antenna-radio-p01] Antennas are required by any radio receiver or transmitter to couple its electrical connection to the electromagnetic field.
[src:ferrite-magnet/antenna-radio-p01] Radio waves are electromagnetic waves that carry signals through space at the speed of light; in free space they propagate without material absorption, apart from geometric spreading loss.
[src:ferrite-magnet/antenna-radio-p01] Antennas can be classified as omnidirectional, radiating energy approximately equally in all horizontal directions, or directional, where radio waves are concentrated in some direction(s).
[src:ferrite-magnet/antenna-radio-p01] A so-called beam antenna is *unidirectional* – designed for maximum response in the direction of the remote station they are aligned with – whereas many other antennas are intended to respond to stations in several directions, but are not truly omnidirectional.
[src:ferrite-magnet/antenna-radio-p01] Since antennas obey *reciprocity*, the same radiation pattern applies both to transmission as well as reception of radio waves.
[src:ferrite-magnet/antenna-radio-p01] A hypothetical antenna that radiates equally in all directions (vertical as well as all horizontal angles) is called an *isotropic radiator*; however, *exact* uniformity cannot be accomplished in practical antennas, and is only rarely desired (e.g. emergency antennas for spacecraft).
[src:ferrite-magnet/antenna-radio-p01] Rather, for most terrestrial communications, there is an advantage in *reducing* radiation toward the sky or ground in favor of horizontal direction(s).
[src:ferrite-magnet/antenna-radio-p01] Several dipole elements of slightly different lengths can be stacked in parallel, into an antenna array such as the Yagi–Uda in order to focus their radiation into a single horizontal direction, perpendicular to the stack, thus termed a *beam antenna*.
[src:ferrite-magnet/antenna-radio-p01] A half‑wave dipole antenna is a balanced element, with equal and opposite voltages and currents at its two terminals, and serves as a simple reference for analyzing many other antenna designs.
[src:ferrite-magnet/antenna-radio-p01] The vertical antenna is a *monopole* antenna, not balanced with respect to ground.
[src:ferrite-magnet/antenna-radio-p01] The ground (or any large conductive surface) plays the role of the second conductor of a monopole.
[src:ferrite-magnet/antenna-radio-p01] Since monopole antennas rely on a conductive surface, they may be mounted with a *ground plane* to approximate the effect of being mounted on the Earth's surface.
[src:ferrite-magnet/antenna-radio-p01] More complex antennas increase the directivity of the antenna.
[src:ferrite-magnet/antenna-radio-p01] Additional elements in the antenna structure, which need not be directly connected to the receiver or transmitter, increase its directionality.
[src:ferrite-magnet/antenna-radio-p01] Antenna "gain" describes the concentration of radiated power into a particular solid angle of space.
[src:ferrite-magnet/antenna-radio-p01] Unlike amplifier gain, which generally implies a net increase in signal power, antenna gain reflects a redistribution of power so that more is radiated in some directions and less in others, without increasing the total radiated power.
[src:ferrite-magnet/antenna-radio-p01] Unlike amplifiers, antennas are electrically "passive" devices which conserve total power, and there is no increase in total power above that delivered from the power source (the transmitter), only improved distribution of that fixed total.
[src:ferrite-magnet/antenna-radio-p01] A phased array consists of two or more simple antennas which are connected together through an electrical network.
[src:ferrite-magnet/antenna-radio-p01] This often involves a number of parallel dipole antennas with a certain spacing.
[src:ferrite-magnet/antenna-radio-p01] Depending on the relative phase introduced by the network, the same combination of dipole antennas can operate as a "broadside array" (directional normal to a line connecting the elements) or as an "end-fire array" (directional along the line connecting the elements).
[src:ferrite-magnet/antenna-radio-p01] Antenna arrays may employ any basic (omnidirectional or weakly directional) antenna type, such as dipole, loop or slot antennas.
[src:ferrite-magnet/antenna-radio-p01] Log‑periodic and other frequency‑independent antennas employ self‑similar structures in order to operate effectively over a wide range of frequencies (i.e., with wide bandwidth).
[src:ferrite-magnet/antenna-radio-p01] The most familiar example is the log-periodic dipole array which can be seen as a number (typically 10 to 20) of connected dipole elements with progressive lengths in an endfire array making it rather directional; it finds use especially as a rooftop antenna for television reception.
[src:ferrite-magnet/antenna-radio-p01] On the other hand, a Yagi–Uda antenna (or simply "Yagi"), with a somewhat similar appearance, has only one dipole element with an electrical connection; the other parasitic elements interact with the electromagnetic field in order to realize a highly directional antenna but with a narrow bandwidth.
[src:ferrite-magnet/antenna-radio-p01] Even greater directionality can be obtained using *aperture antennas* such as the parabolic reflector or horn antenna.
[src:ferrite-magnet/antenna-radio-p01] Since high directivity in an antenna depends on it being large compared to the wavelength, highly directional antennas (thus with high antenna gain) become more practical at higher frequencies (UHF and above).
[src:ferrite-magnet/antenna-radio-p01] At low frequencies (such as AM broadcast), arrays of vertical towers are used to achieve directionality and they will occupy large areas of land.
[src:ferrite-magnet/antenna-radio-p01] For reception, a long Beverage antenna can have significant directivity.
[src:ferrite-magnet/antenna-radio-p01] For non directional portable use, a short vertical antenna or small loop antenna works well, with the main design challenge being that of impedance matching.
[src:ferrite-magnet/antenna-radio-p01] With a vertical antenna a *loading coil* at the base of the antenna may be employed to cancel the reactive component of impedance; small loop antennas are tuned with parallel capacitors for this purpose.
[src:ferrite-magnet/antenna-radio-p01] An antenna *lead-in* is the transmission line, or feed line, that connects the antenna to a transmitter or receiver.
[src:ferrite-magnet/antenna-radio-p01] The "antenna feed" may refer to all components connecting the antenna to the transmitter or receiver, such as an impedance matching network in addition to the transmission line.
[src:ferrite-magnet/antenna-radio-p01] A microwave antenna may also be fed directly from a waveguide in place of a (conductive) transmission line.
[src:ferrite-magnet/antenna-radio-p01] An antenna counterpoise, or ground plane, is a structure of conductive material which improves or substitutes for the ground.
[src:ferrite-magnet/antenna-radio-p01] It may be connected to or insulated from the natural ground.
[src:ferrite-magnet/antenna-radio-p01] In a monopole antenna, this aids in the function of the natural ground, particularly where variations (or limitations) of the characteristics of the natural ground interfere with its proper function.
[src:ferrite-magnet/antenna-radio-p01] Such a structure is normally connected to the return connection of an unbalanced transmission line such as the shield of a coaxial cable.
[src:ferrite-magnet/antenna-radio-p01] An electromagnetic wave refractor in some aperture antennas is a component which due to its shape and position functions to selectively delay or advance portions of the electromagnetic wavefront passing through it.
[src:ferrite-magnet/antenna-radio-p01] The refractor alters the spatial characteristics of the wave on one side relative to the other side.
[src:ferrite-magnet/antenna-radio-p01] It can, for instance, bring the wave to a focus or alter the wave front in other ways, generally in order to maximize the directivity of the antenna system.
[src:ferrite-magnet/antenna-radio-p01] This is the radio equivalent of an optical lens.
[src:ferrite-magnet/antenna-radio-p01] An antenna coupling network is a passive network (generally a combination of inductive and capacitive circuit elements) used for impedance matching in between the antenna and the transmitter or receiver.
[src:ferrite-magnet/antenna-radio-p01] This may be used to minimize losses on the feed line, by reducing transmission line's standing wave ratio, and to present the transmitter or receiver with a standard resistive impedance needed for its optimum operation.
[src:ferrite-magnet/antenna-radio-p01] The feed point location(s) is selected, and antenna elements electrically similar to tuner components may be incorporated in the antenna structure itself, to improve the match.
[src:ferrite-magnet/antenna-radio-p01] It is a fundamental property of antennas that most of the electrical characteristics of an antenna, such as those described in the next section (e.g. gain, radiation pattern, impedance, bandwidth, resonant frequency and polarization), are the same whether the antenna is transmitting or receiving.
[src:ferrite-magnet/antenna-radio-p01] This equivalence follows reciprocity theorem of electromagnetics.
[src:ferrite-magnet/antenna-radio-p01] Therefore, in discussions of antenna properties no distinction is usually made between receiving and transmitting terminology, and the antenna can be viewed as either transmitting or receiving, whichever is more convenient.
[src:ferrite-magnet/antenna-radio-p01] A necessary condition for the aforementioned reciprocity property is that the materials in the antenna and transmission medium are linear and reciprocal.
[src:ferrite-magnet/antenna-radio-p01] *Reciprocal* (or *bilateral*) means that the material has the same response to an electric current or magnetic field in one direction, as it has to the field or current in the opposite direction.
[src:ferrite-magnet/antenna-radio-p01] Most materials used in antennas meet these conditions, but some microwave antennas use high-tech components such as isolators and circulators, made of nonreciprocal materials such as ferrite.
[src:ferrite-magnet/antenna-radio-p01] These can be used to give the antenna a different behavior on receiving than it has on transmitting, which can be useful in applications like radar.
[src:ferrite-magnet/antenna-radio-p01] The majority of antenna designs are based on the *resonance* principle.
[src:ferrite-magnet/antenna-radio-p01] This relies on the behaviour of moving electrons, which reflect off surfaces where the dielectric constant changes, in a fashion similar to the way light reflects when optical properties change.
[src:ferrite-magnet/antenna-radio-p01] In these designs, the reflective surface is created by the end of a conductor, normally a thin metal wire or rod, which in the simplest case has a *feed point* at one end where it is connected to a transmission line.
[src:ferrite-magnet/antenna-radio-p01] The conductor, or *element*, is aligned with the electrical field of the desired signal, normally meaning it is perpendicular to the line from the antenna to the source (or receiver in the case of a broadcast antenna).
[src:ferrite-magnet/antenna-radio-p01] The radio signal's electric component induces a voltage in the conductor.
[src:ferrite-magnet/antenna-radio-p01] This causes an electrical current to begin flowing in the direction of the signal's instantaneous field.
[src:ferrite-magnet/antenna-radio-p01] When the resulting current reaches the end of the conductor, it reflects, which is equivalent to a 180 degree change in phase.
[src:ferrite-magnet/antenna-radio-p01] If the conductor is ⁠ 1 /4⁠ of a wavelength long, current from the feed point will undergo 90 degree phase change by the time it reaches the end of the conductor, reflect through 180 degrees, and then another 90 degrees as it travels back.
[src:ferrite-magnet/antenna-radio-p01] That means it has undergone a total 360 degree phase change, returning it to the original signal.
[src:ferrite-magnet/antenna-radio-p01] The current in the element thus adds to the current being created from the source at that instant.
[src:ferrite-magnet/antenna-radio-p01] This process creates a standing wave in the conductor, with the maximum current at the feed.
[src:ferrite-magnet/antenna-radio-p01] The ordinary half-wave dipole is probably the most widely used antenna design.
[src:ferrite-magnet/antenna-radio-p01] This consists of two ⁠ 1 /4⁠ wavelength elements arranged end-to-end, and lying along essentially the same axis (or *collinear*), each feeding one side of a two-conductor transmission wire.
[src:ferrite-magnet/antenna-radio-p01] The physical arrangement of the two elements places them 180 degrees out of phase, which means that at any given instant one of the elements is driving current into the transmission line while the other is pulling it out.
[src:ferrite-magnet/antenna-radio-p01] The monopole antenna is essentially one half of the half-wave dipole, a single ⁠ 1 /4⁠ wavelength element with the other side connected to ground or an equivalent ground plane (or *counterpoise*).
[src:ferrite-magnet/antenna-radio-p01] Monopoles, which are one-half the size of a dipole, are common for long-wavelength radio signals where a dipole would be impractically large.
[src:ferrite-magnet/antenna-radio-p01] Another common design is the folded dipole which consists of two (or more) half-wave dipoles placed side by side and connected at their ends but only one of which is driven.
[src:ferrite-magnet/antenna-radio-p01] The standing wave forms with this desired pattern at the design operating frequency, fo, and antennas are normally designed to be this size.
[src:ferrite-magnet/antenna-radio-p01] However, feeding that element with 3 fo (whose wavelength is ⁠ 1 /3⁠ that of fo) will also lead to a standing wave pattern.
[src:ferrite-magnet/antenna-radio-p01] Thus, an antenna element is *also* resonant when its length is ⁠ 3 /4⁠ of a wavelength.
[src:ferrite-magnet/antenna-radio-p01] This is true for all odd multiples of ⁠ 1 /4⁠ wavelength.
[src:ferrite-magnet/antenna-radio-p01] This allows some flexibility of design in terms of antenna lengths and feed points.
[src:ferrite-magnet/antenna-radio-p01] Antennas used in such a fashion are known to be *harmonically operated*.
[src:ferrite-magnet/antenna-radio-p01] Resonant antennas usually use a linear conductor (or *element*), or pair of such elements, each of which is about a quarter of the wavelength in length (an odd multiple of quarter wavelengths will also be resonant).
[src:ferrite-magnet/antenna-radio-p01] Antennas that are required to be small compared to the wavelength sacrifice efficiency and cannot be very directional.
[src:ferrite-magnet/antenna-radio-p01] Since wavelengths are so small at higher frequencies (UHF, microwaves) trading off performance to obtain a smaller physical size is usually not required.
[src:ferrite-magnet/antenna-radio-p01] The quarter-wave elements imitate a series-resonant electrical element due to the standing wave present along the conductor.
[src:ferrite-magnet/antenna-radio-p01] At the resonant frequency, the standing wave has a current peak and voltage node (minimum) at the feed.
[src:ferrite-magnet/antenna-radio-p01] In electrical terms, this means that at that position, the element has minimum impedance magnitude, generating the maximum current for minimum voltage.
[src:ferrite-magnet/antenna-radio-p01] This is the ideal situation, because it produces the maximum output for the minimum input, producing the highest possible efficiency.
[src:ferrite-magnet/antenna-radio-p01] Contrary to an ideal (lossless) series-resonant circuit, a finite resistance remains (corresponding to the relatively small voltage at the feed-point) due to the antenna's resistance to radiating, as well as any conventional electrical losses from producing heat.
[src:ferrite-magnet/antenna-radio-p01] Recall that a current will reflect when there are changes in the electrical properties of the material.
[src:ferrite-magnet/antenna-radio-p01] This leads to the concept of impedance matching, the design of the overall system of antenna and transmission line so the impedance is as close as possible, thereby reducing these losses.
[src:ferrite-magnet/antenna-radio-p01] Impedance matching is accomplished by a circuit called an antenna tuner or impedance matching network between the transmitter and antenna.
[src:ferrite-magnet/antenna-radio-p01] The impedance match between the feedline and antenna is measured by a parameter called the standing wave ratio (SWR) on the feedline.
[src:ferrite-magnet/antenna-radio-p01] Consider a half-wave dipole designed to work with signals with wavelength 1 m, meaning the antenna would be approximately 50 cm from tip to tip.
[src:ferrite-magnet/antenna-radio-p01] If the element has a length-to-diameter ratio of 1000, it will have an inherent impedance of about 63 ohms resistive.
[src:ferrite-magnet/antenna-radio-p01] Using the appropriate transmission wire or balun, we match that resistance to ensure minimum signal reflection.
[src:ferrite-magnet/antenna-radio-p01] Feeding that antenna with a current of 1 Ampere will require 63 Volts, and the antenna will radiate 63 Watts (ignoring losses) of radio frequency power.
[src:ferrite-magnet/antenna-radio-p01] Now consider the case when the antenna is fed a signal with a wavelength of 1.25 m; in this case the current induced by the signal would arrive at the antenna's feedpoint out-of-phase with the signal, causing the net current to drop while the voltage remains the same.
[src:ferrite-magnet/antenna-radio-p01] Electrically this appears to be a very high impedance.
[src:ferrite-magnet/antenna-radio-p01] The antenna and transmission line no longer have the same impedance, and the signal will be reflected back into the antenna, reducing output.
[src:ferrite-magnet/antenna-radio-p01] This could be addressed by changing the matching system between the antenna and transmission line, but that solution only works well at the new design frequency.
[src:ferrite-magnet/antenna-radio-p01] The result is that the resonant antenna will efficiently feed a signal into the transmission line only when the source signal's frequency is close to that of the design frequency of the antenna, or one of the resonant multiples.
[src:ferrite-magnet/antenna-radio-p01] This makes resonant antenna designs inherently narrow-band: Only useful for a small range of frequencies centered around the resonance(s).
[src:ferrite-magnet/antenna-radio-p01] It is possible to use simple impedance matching techniques to allow the use of monopole or dipole antennas substantially shorter than the ⁠ 1 /4⁠ or ⁠ 1 /2⁠ wave, respectively, at which they are resonant.
[src:ferrite-magnet/antenna-radio-p01] Sometimes the resulting (lower) electrical resonant frequency of such a system (antenna plus matching network) is described using the concept of *electrical length*.
[src:ferrite-magnet/antenna-radio-p01] An antenna operated at a lower frequency than its self‑resonant frequency is then called an *electrically short antenna*.
[src:ferrite-magnet/antenna-radio-p01] For example, at 30 MHz (10 m wavelength) a true resonant ⁠ 1 /4⁠ wave monopole would be almost 2.5 meters long, and using an antenna only 1.5 meters tall would require the addition of a loading coil.
[src:ferrite-magnet/antenna-radio-p01] Then it may be said that the coil has lengthened the antenna to achieve an electrical length of 2.5 meters.
[src:ferrite-magnet/antenna-radio-p01] However, the resulting resistive impedance achieved will be quite a bit lower than that of a true ⁠ 1 /4⁠ wave (resonant) monopole, often requiring further impedance matching (a transformer) to the desired transmission line.
[src:ferrite-magnet/antenna-radio-p01] For ever shorter antennas (requiring greater "electrical lengthening") the radiation resistance plummets (approximately according to the square of the antenna length), so that the mismatch due to a net reactance away from the electrical resonance worsens.
[src:ferrite-magnet/antenna-radio-p01] Or one could as well say that the equivalent resonant circuit of the antenna system has a higher Q factor and thus a reduced bandwidth, which can even become inadequate for the transmitted signal's spectrum.
[src:ferrite-magnet/antenna-radio-p01] Resistive losses due to the loading coil, relative to the decreased radiation resistance, entail a reduced electrical efficiency, which can be of great concern for a transmitting antenna, but bandwidth is the major factor that sets the size of antennas at 1 MHz and lower frequencies.
[src:ferrite-magnet/antenna-radio-p01] The power flux density of the field from a transmitting antenna decreases with distance according to the inverse-square law, reflecting the geometrical spreading of the wave.
[src:ferrite-magnet/antenna-radio-p01] For a given incoming flux, the power captured by a receiving antenna is proportional to its *effective area*.
[src:ferrite-magnet/antenna-radio-p01] A half‑wave dipole, for example, has an effective area of about 0.13 λ2 when viewed from broadside.
[src:ferrite-magnet/antenna-radio-p01] For an already efficient antenna design, the effective area (and thus gain) in a given direction can be increased only by reducing the gain in other directions.
[src:ferrite-magnet/antenna-radio-p01] If a half-wave dipole is not connected to an external circuit but rather shorted out at the feedpoint, then it becomes a resonant half-wave element which efficiently produces a standing wave in response to an impinging radio wave.
[src:ferrite-magnet/antenna-radio-p01] Because there is no load to absorb that power, it retransmits all of that power, possibly with a phase shift which is critically dependent on the element's exact length.
[src:ferrite-magnet/antenna-radio-p01] Thus such a conductor can be arranged in order to transmit a second copy of a transmitter's signal in order to affect the radiation pattern (and feedpoint impedance) of the element electrically connected to the transmitter.
[src:ferrite-magnet/antenna-radio-p01] Antenna elements used in this way are known as passive radiators.
[src:ferrite-magnet/antenna-radio-p01] A Yagi–Uda array uses passive elements to greatly increase gain in one direction (at the expense of other directions).
[src:ferrite-magnet/antenna-radio-p01] A number of parallel approximately half-wave elements (of very specific lengths) are situated parallel to each other, at specific positions, along a boom; the boom is only for support and not involved electrically.
[src:ferrite-magnet/antenna-radio-p01] Only one of the elements is electrically connected to the transmitter or receiver, while the remaining elements are passive.
[src:ferrite-magnet/antenna-radio-p01] The Yagi produces a fairly large gain (depending on the number of passive elements) and is widely used as a directional antenna with an antenna rotor to control the direction of its beam.
[src:ferrite-magnet/antenna-radio-p01] It suffers from having a rather limited bandwidth, restricting its use to certain applications.
[src:ferrite-magnet/antenna-radio-p01] What's more, a phased array can be made "steerable", that is, by changing the phases applied to each element the radiation pattern can be shifted *without* physically moving the antenna elements.
[src:ferrite-magnet/antenna-radio-p01] When a radio wave hits a large conducting sheet it is reflected (with the phase of the electric field reversed) just as a mirror reflects light.
[src:ferrite-magnet/antenna-radio-p01] Placing such a reflector behind an otherwise non-directional antenna will insure that the power that would have gone in its direction is redirected toward the desired direction, increasing the antenna's gain by a factor of at least 2.
[src:ferrite-magnet/antenna-radio-p01] Likewise, a corner reflector can insure that all of the antenna's power is concentrated in only one quadrant of space (or less) with a consequent increase in gain.
[src:ferrite-magnet/antenna-radio-p01] Practically speaking, the reflector need not be a solid metal sheet, but can consist of a curtain of rods aligned with the antenna's polarization; this greatly reduces the reflector's weight and wind load.
[src:ferrite-magnet/antenna-radio-p01] Specular reflection of radio waves is also employed in a parabolic reflector antenna, in which a *curved* reflecting surface effects focussing of an incoming wave toward a so-called feed antenna; this results in an antenna system with an effective area comparable to the size of the reflector itself.
[src:ferrite-magnet/antenna-radio-p01] Other concepts from geometrical optics are also employed in antenna technology, such as with the lens antenna.
[src:ferrite-magnet/antenna-radio-p01] The antenna's power gain (or simply "gain") also takes into account the antenna's efficiency, and is often the primary figure of merit.
[src:ferrite-magnet/antenna-radio-p01] Antennas are characterized by a number of performance measures which a user would be concerned with in selecting or designing an antenna for a particular application.
[src:ferrite-magnet/antenna-radio-p01] A plot of the directional characteristics in the space surrounding the antenna is its *radiation pattern*.
[src:ferrite-magnet/antenna-radio-p01] The frequency range or *bandwidth* over which an antenna functions well can be very wide (as in a log-periodic antenna) or narrow (as in a small loop antenna); outside this range the antenna impedance becomes a poor match to the transmission line and transmitter (or receiver).
[src:ferrite-magnet/antenna-radio-p01] Use of the antenna well away from its design frequency affects its radiation pattern, reducing its directive gain.
[src:ferrite-magnet/antenna-radio-p01] Generally an antenna will not have a feed-point impedance that matches that of a transmission line; a matching network between antenna terminals and the transmission line will improve power transfer to the antenna.
[src:ferrite-magnet/antenna-radio-p01] A non-adjustable matching network will most likely place further limits the usable bandwidth of the antenna system.
[src:ferrite-magnet/antenna-radio-p01] It may be desirable to use tubular elements, instead of thin wires, to make an antenna; these will allow a greater bandwidth.
[src:ferrite-magnet/antenna-radio-p01] Or, several thin wires can be grouped in a *cage* to simulate a thicker element.
[src:ferrite-magnet/antenna-radio-p01] This widens the bandwidth of the resonance.
[src:ferrite-magnet/antenna-radio-p01] Amateur radio antennas that operate at several frequency bands which are widely separated from each other may connect elements resonant at those different frequencies in parallel.
[src:ferrite-magnet/antenna-radio-p01] Most of the transmitter's power will flow into the resonant element while the others present a high impedance.
[src:ferrite-magnet/antenna-radio-p01] Another solution uses *traps*, parallel resonant circuits which are strategically placed in breaks created in long antenna elements.
[src:ferrite-magnet/antenna-radio-p01] When used at the trap's particular resonant frequency the trap presents a very high impedance (parallel resonance) effectively truncating the element at the location of the trap; if positioned correctly, the truncated element makes a proper resonant antenna at the trap frequency.
[src:ferrite-magnet/antenna-radio-p01] At substantially higher or lower frequencies the trap allows the full length of the broken element to be employed, but with a resonant frequency shifted by the net reactance added by the trap.
[src:ferrite-magnet/antenna-radio-p01] The bandwidth characteristics of a resonant antenna element can be characterized according to its *Q* where the resistance involved is the radiation resistance, which represents the emission of energy from the resonant antenna to free space.
[src:ferrite-magnet/antenna-radio-p01] The *Q* of a narrow band antenna can be as high as 15.
[src:ferrite-magnet/antenna-radio-p01] On the other hand, the reactance at the same off-resonant frequency of one using thick elements is much less, consequently resulting in a *Q* as low as 5.
[src:ferrite-magnet/antenna-radio-p01] These two antennas may perform equivalently at the resonant frequency, but the second antenna will perform over a bandwidth 3 times as wide as the antenna consisting of a thin conductor.
[src:ferrite-magnet/antenna-radio-p01] Antennas for use over much broader frequency ranges are achieved using further techniques.
[src:ferrite-magnet/antenna-radio-p01] Adjustment of a matching network can, in principle, allow for any antenna to be matched at any frequency.
[src:ferrite-magnet/antenna-radio-p01] Thus the small loop antenna built into most AM broadcast (medium wave) receivers has a very narrow bandwidth, but is tuned using a parallel capacitance which is adjusted according to the receiver tuning.
[src:ferrite-magnet/antenna-radio-p01] On the other hand, log-periodic antennas are *not* resonant at any single frequency but can (in principle) be built to attain similar characteristics (including feedpoint impedance) over any frequency range.
[src:ferrite-magnet/antenna-radio-p01] These are therefore commonly used (in the form of directional log-periodic dipole arrays) as television antennas.
[src:ferrite-magnet/antenna-radio-p01] Gain is a parameter which measures the degree of directivity of the antenna's radiation pattern.
[src:ferrite-magnet/antenna-radio-p01] A high-gain antenna will radiate most of its power in a particular direction, while a low-gain antenna will radiate over a wide angle.
[src:ferrite-magnet/antenna-radio-p01] High-gain antennas have the advantage of longer range and better signal quality, but must be aimed carefully at the other antenna.
[src:ferrite-magnet/antenna-radio-p01] An example of a high-gain antenna is a parabolic dish such as a satellite television antenna.
[src:ferrite-magnet/antenna-radio-p01] Low-gain antennas have shorter range, but the orientation of the antenna is relatively unimportant.
[src:ferrite-magnet/antenna-radio-p01] An example of a low-gain antenna is the whip antenna found on portable radios and cordless phones.
[src:ferrite-magnet/antenna-radio-p01] Antenna gain should not be confused with amplifier gain, a separate parameter measuring the increase in signal power due to an amplifying device placed at the front-end of the system, such as a low-noise amplifier.
[src:ferrite-magnet/antenna-radio-p01] The *effective area* or effective aperture of a receiving antenna expresses the portion of the power of a passing electromagnetic wave which the antenna delivers to its terminals, expressed in terms of an equivalent area.
[src:ferrite-magnet/antenna-radio-p01] For instance, if a radio wave passing a given location has a flux of 1 pW / m2 (10−12 Watts per square meter) and an antenna has an effective area of 12 m2, then the antenna would deliver 12 pW of RF power to the receiver (30 microvolts RMS at 75 ohms).
[src:ferrite-magnet/antenna-radio-p01] Since the receiving antenna is not equally sensitive to signals received from all directions, the effective area is a function of the direction to the source.
[src:ferrite-magnet/antenna-radio-p01] Due to reciprocity (discussed above) the gain of an antenna used for transmitting must be proportional to its effective area when used for receiving.
[src:ferrite-magnet/antenna-radio-p01] Consider an antenna with no loss, that is, one whose electrical efficiency is 100%.
[src:ferrite-magnet/antenna-radio-p01] It can be shown that its effective area averaged over all directions must be equal to λ2/4π, the wavelength squared divided by 4π.
[src:ferrite-magnet/antenna-radio-p01] Gain is defined such that the average gain over all directions for an antenna with 100% electrical efficiency is equal to 1.
[src:ferrite-magnet/antenna-radio-p01] For an antenna with an efficiency of less than 100%, both the effective area and gain are reduced by that same amount.
[src:ferrite-magnet/antenna-radio-p01] Therefore, the above relationship between gain and effective area still holds.
[src:ferrite-magnet/antenna-radio-p01] These are thus two different ways of expressing the same quantity.
[src:ferrite-magnet/antenna-radio-p01] *A*eff is especially convenient when computing the power that would be received by an antenna of a specified gain, as illustrated by the above example.
[src:ferrite-magnet/antenna-radio-p01] The radiation pattern of an antenna is a plot of the relative field strength of the radio waves emitted by the antenna at different angles in the far field.
[src:ferrite-magnet/antenna-radio-p01] It is typically represented by a three-dimensional graph, or polar plots of the horizontal and vertical cross sections.
[src:ferrite-magnet/antenna-radio-p01] The pattern of an ideal isotropic antenna, which radiates equally in all directions, would look like a sphere.
[src:ferrite-magnet/antenna-radio-p01] Many nondirectional antennas, such as monopoles and dipoles, emit equal power in all horizontal directions, with the power dropping off at higher and lower angles; this is called an omnidirectional pattern and when plotted looks like a torus or donut.
[src:ferrite-magnet/antenna-radio-p01] The radiation of many antennas shows a pattern of maxima or "*lobes*" at various angles, separated by "*nulls*", angles where the radiation falls to zero.
[src:ferrite-magnet/antenna-radio-p01] This is because the radio waves emitted by different parts of the antenna typically interfere, causing maxima at angles where the radio waves arrive at distant points in phase, and zero radiation at other angles where the radio waves arrive out of phase.
[src:ferrite-magnet/antenna-radio-p01] In a directional antenna designed to project radio waves in a particular direction, the lobe in that direction is designed larger than the others and is called the "*main lobe*".
[src:ferrite-magnet/antenna-radio-p01] The other lobes usually represent unwanted radiation and are called "*sidelobes*".
[src:ferrite-magnet/antenna-radio-p01] The axis through the main lobe is called the "*principal axis*" or "*boresight axis*".
[src:ferrite-magnet/antenna-radio-p01] The polar radiation patterns of Yagi antennas become narrower, and their directivity (and thus gain) increases, when they are designed for a relatively narrow frequency range, as compared with wideband designs.
[src:ferrite-magnet/antenna-radio-p01] The space surrounding an antenna can be divided into three concentric regions: The reactive near-field (also called the inductive near-field), the radiating near-field (Fresnel region) and the far-field (Fraunhofer) regions.
[src:ferrite-magnet/antenna-radio-p01] These regions are useful to identify the field structure in each, although the transitions between them are gradual; there are no clear boundaries.
[src:ferrite-magnet/antenna-radio-p01] The orientation and physical structure of an antenna determine the *polarization* of the electric field of the radio wave transmitted by it.
[src:ferrite-magnet/antenna-radio-p01] For instance, an antenna composed of a linear conductor (such as a dipole or whip antenna) oriented vertically will result in vertical polarization; if turned on its side the same antenna's polarization will be horizontal.
[src:ferrite-magnet/antenna-radio-p01] In the most general case, polarization is elliptical, meaning that over each cycle the electric field vector traces out an ellipse.
[src:ferrite-magnet/antenna-radio-p01] Two special cases are linear polarization (the ellipse collapses into a line) as discussed above, and circular polarization (in which the two axes of the ellipse are equal).
[src:ferrite-magnet/antenna-radio-p01] In linear polarization the electric field of the radio wave oscillates along one direction.
[src:ferrite-magnet/antenna-radio-p01] In circular polarization, the electric field of the radio wave rotates around the axis of propagation.
[src:ferrite-magnet/antenna-radio-p01] Circular or elliptically polarized radio waves are designated as right-handed or left-handed using the "thumb in the direction of the propagation" rule.
[src:ferrite-magnet/antenna-radio-p01] Note that for circular polarization, optical researchers use the opposite right-hand rule from the one used by radio engineers.
[src:ferrite-magnet/antenna-radio-p01] It is best for the receiving antenna to match the polarization of the transmitted wave for optimum reception.
[src:ferrite-magnet/antenna-radio-p01] Otherwise there will be a loss of signal strength: when a linearly polarized antenna receives linearly polarized radiation at a relative angle of θ, then there will be a power loss of cos2θ .
[src:ferrite-magnet/antenna-radio-p01] A circularly polarized antenna can be used to equally well match vertical or horizontal linear polarizations, suffering a 3 dB signal reduction.
[src:ferrite-magnet/antenna-radio-p01] However it will be blind to a circularly polarized signal of the opposite orientation.
[src:ferrite-magnet/antenna-radio-p01] Maximum power transfer requires matching the impedance of an antenna system (as seen looking into the transmission line) to the complex conjugate of the impedance of the receiver or transmitter.
[src:ferrite-magnet/antenna-radio-p01] The intended impedance is normally resistive, but a transmitter (and some receivers) may have limited additional adjustments to cancel a certain amount of reactance, in order to "tweak" the match.
[src:ferrite-magnet/antenna-radio-p01] The match is sought to minimize the amplitude of standing waves (measured via the standing wave ratio; SWR) that a mismatch raises on the line, and the increase in transmission line losses it entails.
[src:ferrite-magnet/antenna-radio-p01] Antenna tuning, in the strict sense of modifying the antenna itself, generally refers only to cancellation of any reactance seen at the antenna terminals, leaving only a resistive impedance which might or might not be exactly the desired impedance (that of the available transmission line).
[src:ferrite-magnet/antenna-radio-p01] Although an antenna may be designed to have a purely resistive feedpoint impedance (such as a dipole 97% of a half wavelength long) at just one frequency, this will very likely not be exactly true at other frequencies that the antenna is eventually used for.
[src:ferrite-magnet/antenna-radio-p01] In most cases, in principle the physical length of the antenna can be "trimmed" to obtain a pure resistance, although this is rarely convenient.
[src:ferrite-magnet/antenna-radio-p01] On the other hand, the addition of a contrary inductance or capacitance can be used to cancel a residual capacitive or inductive reactance, respectively, and may be more convenient than lowering and trimming or extending the antenna, then hoisting it back.
[src:ferrite-magnet/antenna-radio-p01] In addition to those reactance-neutralizing add-ons, antennas of any kind may include a transformer and / or transformer balun at their feedpoint, to change the resistive part of the impedance to more nearly match the feedline's characteristic impedance.
[src:ferrite-magnet/antenna-radio-p01] An additional problem is matching the remaining resistive impedance to the characteristic impedance of the transmission line: A general impedance matching network (an "antenna tuner" or ATU) will have at least two adjustable elements to correct both components of impedance.
[src:ferrite-magnet/antenna-radio-p01] Any matching network will have both power losses and power restrictions when used for transmitting.
[src:ferrite-magnet/antenna-radio-p01] Commercial antennas are generally designed to approximately match standard 50 Ohm coaxial cables, at standard frequencies; the design expectation is that a matching network will be merely used to 'tweak' any residual mismatch.
[src:ferrite-magnet/antenna-radio-p01] In some cases matching is done in a more extreme manner, not simply to cancel a small amount of residual reactance, but to resonate an antenna whose resonance frequency is quite different from the intended frequency of operation.
[src:ferrite-magnet/antenna-radio-p01] The physically large inductor at the base of the antenna has an inductive reactance which is the opposite of the capacitative reactance that the short vertical antenna has at the desired operating frequency.
[src:ferrite-magnet/antenna-radio-p01] (usually, but not always, for receiving) at a relatively low frequency, where it appears almost as a pure inductor.
[src:ferrite-magnet/antenna-radio-p01] to produce a better-matched feedpoint resistance.
[src:ferrite-magnet/antenna-radio-p01] The loop is resonated by a coupled tuning capacitor, which is configured to match the receiver's tuning, in order to keep the antenna resonant at the chosen receive frequency over the AM broadcast band.
[src:ferrite-magnet/antenna-radio-p01] Ground reflections is one of the common types of multipath.
[src:ferrite-magnet/antenna-radio-p01] The radiation pattern and even the driving point impedance of an antenna can be influenced by the dielectric constant and especially conductivity of nearby objects.
[src:ferrite-magnet/antenna-radio-p01] For a terrestrial antenna, the ground is usually one such object of importance.
[src:ferrite-magnet/antenna-radio-p01] The antenna's height above the ground, as well as the electrical properties (permittivity and conductivity) of the ground, can then be important.
[src:ferrite-magnet/antenna-radio-p01] Also, in the particular case of a monopole antenna, the ground (or an artificial ground plane) serves as the return connection for the antenna current thus having an additional effect, particularly on the impedance seen by the feed line.
[src:ferrite-magnet/antenna-radio-p01] When an electromagnetic wave strikes a plane surface such as the ground, part of the wave is transmitted into the ground and part of it is reflected, according to the Fresnel coefficients.
[src:ferrite-magnet/antenna-radio-p01] If the ground is a very good conductor then almost all of the wave is reflected (180° out of phase), whereas a ground modeled as a (lossy) dielectric can absorb a large amount of the wave's power.
[src:ferrite-magnet/antenna-radio-p01] The power remaining in the reflected wave, and the phase shift upon reflection, strongly depend on the wave's angle of incidence and polarization.
[src:ferrite-magnet/antenna-radio-p01] The dielectric constant and conductivity (or simply the complex dielectric constant) is dependent on the soil type and is a function of frequency.
[src:ferrite-magnet/antenna-radio-p01] At lower mediumwave frequencies the ground acts mainly as a good conductor, which AM broadcast (0.5–1.7 MHz) antennas depend on.
[src:ferrite-magnet/antenna-radio-p01] At frequencies between 3–30 MHz, a large portion of the energy from a horizontally polarized antenna reflects off the ground, with almost total reflection at the grazing angles important for ground wave propagation.
[src:ferrite-magnet/antenna-radio-p01] That reflected wave, with its phase reversed, can either cancel or reinforce the direct wave, depending on the antenna height in wavelengths and elevation angle (for a sky wave).
[src:ferrite-magnet/antenna-radio-p01] On the other hand, vertically polarized radiation is not well reflected by the ground except at grazing incidence or over very highly conducting surfaces such as sea water.
[src:ferrite-magnet/antenna-radio-p01] However the grazing angle reflection important for ground wave propagation, using vertical polarization, is *in phase* with the direct wave, providing a boost of up to 6 dB, as is detailed below.
[src:ferrite-magnet/antenna-radio-p01] At VHF and above (> 30 MHz) the ground becomes a poorer reflector.
[src:ferrite-magnet/antenna-radio-p01] However, for shortwave frequencies, especially below ~15 MHz, it remains a good reflector especially for horizontal polarization and grazing angles of incidence.
[src:ferrite-magnet/antenna-radio-p01] That is important as these higher frequencies usually depend on horizontal line-of-sight propagation (except for satellite communications), the ground then behaving almost as a mirror.
[src:ferrite-magnet/antenna-radio-p01] The net quality of a ground reflection depends on the topography of the surface.
[src:ferrite-magnet/antenna-radio-p01] When the irregularities of the surface are much smaller than the wavelength, the dominant regime is that of specular reflection, and the receiver sees both the real antenna and an image of the antenna under the ground due to reflection.
[src:ferrite-magnet/antenna-radio-p01] But if the ground has irregularities not small compared to the wavelength, reflections will not be coherent but shifted by random phases.
[src:ferrite-magnet/antenna-radio-p01] With shorter wavelengths (higher frequencies), this is generally the case.
[src:ferrite-magnet/antenna-radio-p01] Whenever both the receiving or transmitting antenna are placed at significant heights above the ground (relative to the wavelength), waves reflected specularly by the ground will travel a longer distance than direct waves, inducing a phase shift which can sometimes be significant.
[src:ferrite-magnet/antenna-radio-p01] When a sky wave is launched by such an antenna, that phase shift is always significant unless the antenna is very close to the ground (compared to the wavelength).
[src:ferrite-magnet/antenna-radio-p02] The flow of current in wire antennas is identical to the solution of counter-propagating waves in a single conductor transmission line, which can be solved using the telegrapher's equations.
[src:ferrite-magnet/antenna-radio-p02] Unlike transmission lines, currents in antennas contribute power to the radiated part electromagnetic field, which can be modeled using radiation resistance.
[src:ferrite-magnet/antenna-radio-p02] The combination of the incident and reflected wave, just as in a transmission line, forms a standing wave with a current node at the conductor's end, and a voltage node one-quarter wavelength from the end (if the element is at least that long).
[src:ferrite-magnet/antenna-radio-p02] In a *resonant antenna*, the feedpoint of the antenna is at one of those voltage nodes.
[src:ferrite-magnet/antenna-radio-p02] Due to discrepancies from the simplified version of the transmission line model, the voltage one quarter wavelength from the current node is not exactly zero, but it is near a minimum, and small compared to the much larger voltage at the conductor's end.
[src:ferrite-magnet/antenna-radio-p02] Hence, a feed point matching the antenna at that spot requires a relatively small voltage but large current (the currents from the two waves add in-phase there), thus a relatively low feedpoint impedance.
[src:ferrite-magnet/antenna-radio-p02] Feeding the antenna at other points involves a large voltage, thus a large impedance, and usually one that is primarily reactive (low power factor), which is a terrible impedance match to available transmission lines.
[src:ferrite-magnet/antenna-radio-p02] Therefore, it is usually desired for an antenna to operate as a resonant element with each conductor having a length of one quarter wavelength (or any other odd multiples of a quarter wavelength).
[src:ferrite-magnet/antenna-radio-p02] For instance, a half-wave dipole has two such elements (one connected to each conductor of a balanced transmission line) about one quarter wavelength long.
[src:ferrite-magnet/antenna-radio-p02] Depending on the conductors' diameters, a small deviation from this length is adopted in order to reach the point where the antenna current and the (small) feedpoint voltage are exactly in phase.
[src:ferrite-magnet/antenna-radio-p02] Then the antenna presents a purely resistive impedance, and ideally one close to the characteristic impedance of an available transmission line.
[src:ferrite-magnet/antenna-radio-p02] Despite these useful properties, resonant antennas have the disadvantage that they achieve resonance (purely resistive feedpoint impedance) only at a fundamental frequency, and perhaps some of its harmonics, and the feedpoint resistance is larger at higher-order resonances.
[src:ferrite-magnet/antenna-radio-p02] Therefore, resonant antennas can only achieve their good performance within a limited bandwidth, depending on the Q at the resonance.
[src:ferrite-magnet/antenna-radio-p02] The electric and magnetic fields emanating from a driven antenna element will generally affect the voltages and currents in nearby antennas, antenna elements, or other conductors.
[src:ferrite-magnet/antenna-radio-p02] This is particularly true when the affected conductor is a resonant element (multiple of half-wavelengths in length) at about the same frequency, as is the case where the conductors are all part of the same active or passive antenna array.
[src:ferrite-magnet/antenna-radio-p02] Thus using the mutual impedances calculated for a specific geometry, one can solve for the radiation pattern of a Yagi–Uda antenna or the currents and voltages for each element of a phased array.
[src:ferrite-magnet/antenna-radio-p02] Such an analysis can also describe in detail reflection of radio waves by a ground plane or by a corner reflector and their effect on the impedance (and radiation pattern) of an antenna in its vicinity.
[src:ferrite-magnet/antenna-radio-p02] Often such near-field interactions are undesired and pernicious.
[src:ferrite-magnet/antenna-radio-p02] Currents in random metal objects near a transmitting antenna will often be in poor conductors, causing loss of RF power in addition to unpredictably altering the characteristics of the antenna.
[src:ferrite-magnet/antenna-radio-p02] By careful design, it is possible to reduce the electrical interaction between nearby conductors.
[src:ferrite-magnet/antenna-radio-p02] For instance, the 90 degree angle in between the two dipoles composing the turnstile antenna ensures no interaction between these, allowing these to be driven independently (but actually with the same signal in quadrature phases in the turnstile antenna design).
[src:ferrite-magnet/antenna-radio-p02] Antennas can be classified by operating principles or by their application.
[src:ferrite-magnet/antenna-radio-p02] Different authorities placed antennas in narrower or broader categories.
[src:ferrite-magnet/antenna-radio-p02] These antenna types and others are summarized in greater detail in the overview article, Antenna types, as well as in each of the linked articles in the list above, and in even more detail in articles which those link to.
[src:ferrite-magnet/barium-carbonate] Pyrolysis of barium carbonate gives barium oxide.
[src:ferrite-magnet/barium-carbonate] Barium carbonate is mainly used to remove sulfate impurities from feedstock of the chlor-alkali process.
[src:ferrite-magnet/barium-carbonate] Otherwise it is a common precursor to barium-containing compounds such as ferrites.
[src:ferrite-magnet/barium-carbonate] Barium carbonate is widely used in the ceramics industry as an ingredient in glazes.
[src:ferrite-magnet/barium-carbonate] It acts as a flux, a matting and crystallizing agent and combines with certain colouring oxides to produce unique colours not easily attainable by other means.
[src:ferrite-magnet/barium-carbonate] Its use is somewhat controversial since it can leach from glazes into food and drink.
[src:ferrite-magnet/barium-carbonate] To reduce toxicity concerns, it is often substituted with strontium carbonate, which behaves in a similar way in glazes but is of lower toxicity.
[src:ferrite-magnet/barium-carbonate] In the brick, tile, earthenware and pottery industries barium carbonate is added to clays to precipitate soluble salts (calcium sulfate and magnesium sulfate) that cause efflorescence.
[src:ferrite-magnet/barium-carbonate] It is sometimes used as an "energiser" in the Case-hardening process.
[src:ferrite-magnet/barium] The most common minerals of barium are barite (barium sulfate, BaSO4) and witherite (barium carbonate, BaCO3).
[src:ferrite-magnet/barium] The name *barium* originates from the alchemical derivative "baryta" from Greek βαρὺς (*barys*), meaning 'heavy'.
[src:ferrite-magnet/barium] *Baric* is the adjectival form of barium.
[src:ferrite-magnet/barium] Barium was identified as a new element in 1772, but not reduced to a metal until 1808 with the advent of electrolysis.
[src:ferrite-magnet/barium] Historically, it was used as a getter for vacuum tubes and in oxide form as the emissive coating on indirectly heated cathodes.
[src:ferrite-magnet/barium] It is a component of YBCO (high-temperature superconductors) and electroceramics, and is added to steel and cast iron to reduce the size of carbon grains within the microstructure.
[src:ferrite-magnet/barium] Barium compounds are added to fireworks to impart a green color.
[src:ferrite-magnet/barium] Barium sulfate is used as an insoluble additive to oil well drilling fluid.
[src:ferrite-magnet/barium] In a purer form it is used as X-ray radiocontrast agents for imaging the human gastrointestinal tract.
[src:ferrite-magnet/barium] Water-soluble barium compounds are poisonous and have been used as rodenticides.
[src:ferrite-magnet/barium] Barium is a soft, silvery-white metal, with a slight golden shade when ultrapure.
[src:ferrite-magnet/barium] The silvery-white color of barium metal rapidly vanishes upon oxidation in air yielding a dark gray layer containing the oxide.
[src:ferrite-magnet/barium] Barium has a medium specific weight and high electrical conductivity.
[src:ferrite-magnet/barium] Because barium is difficult to purify, many of its properties have not been accurately determined.
[src:ferrite-magnet/barium] At room temperature and pressure, barium metal adopts a body-centered cubic structure, with a barium–barium distance of 503 picometers, expanding with heating at a rate of approximately 1.8×10−5/°C.
[src:ferrite-magnet/barium] It is a soft metal with a Mohs hardness of 1.25.
[src:ferrite-magnet/barium] The density (3.62 g/cm3) is again intermediate between those of strontium (2.36 g/cm3) and radium (≈5 g/cm3).
[src:ferrite-magnet/barium] Barium is chemically similar to magnesium, calcium, and strontium, but more reactive.
[src:ferrite-magnet/barium] Its compounds are almost invariably found in the +2 oxidation state.
[src:ferrite-magnet/barium] As expected for a highly electropositive metal, barium's reaction with chalcogens is highly exothermic (release energy).
[src:ferrite-magnet/barium] Barium reacts with atmospheric oxygen in air at room temperature.
[src:ferrite-magnet/barium] For this reason, metallic barium is often stored under oil or in an inert atmosphere.
[src:ferrite-magnet/barium] Reactions with other nonmetals, such as carbon, nitrogen, phosphorus, silicon, and hydrogen, proceed upon heating.
[src:ferrite-magnet/barium] Barium reacts with ammonia to form the electride [Ba(NH3)6](e−)2, which near room temperature gives the amide Ba(NH2)2.
[src:ferrite-magnet/barium] Sulfuric acid is a notable exception because passivation stops the reaction by forming the insoluble barium sulfate on the surface.
[src:ferrite-magnet/barium] Barium combines with several other metals, including aluminium, zinc, lead, and tin, forming intermetallic phases and alloys.
[src:ferrite-magnet/barium] Barium salts are typically white when solid and colorless when dissolved.
[src:ferrite-magnet/barium] They are denser than the strontium or calcium analogs (see table; zinc is given for comparison).
[src:ferrite-magnet/barium] Barium hydroxide ("baryta") was known to alchemists, who produced it by heating barium carbonate.
[src:ferrite-magnet/barium] Unlike calcium hydroxide, it absorbs very little CO2 in aqueous solutions and is therefore insensitive to atmospheric fluctuations.
[src:ferrite-magnet/barium] This property is used in calibrating pH equipment.
[src:ferrite-magnet/barium] Barium compounds burn with a green to pale green flame, which is an efficient test to detect a barium compound.
[src:ferrite-magnet/barium] Organobarium compounds are a growing field of knowledge: recently discovered are dialkylbariums and alkylhalobariums.
[src:ferrite-magnet/barium] Barium found in the Earth's crust is a mixture of seven primordial nuclides, barium-130, 132, and 134 through 138.
[src:ferrite-magnet/barium] Barium-130 undergoes very slow radioactive decay to xenon-130 by double beta plus decay, with a half-life of (0.5–2.7)×1021 years (about 1011 times the age of the universe).
[src:ferrite-magnet/barium] Its abundance is about 0.11% that of natural barium.
[src:ferrite-magnet/barium] Though barium-132 can theoretically undergo the same decay, giving xenon-132, experimental evidence has not detected this.
[src:ferrite-magnet/barium] Of the stable isotopes, barium-138 composes 71.7% of all barium; other isotopes have decreasing abundance with decreasing mass number (except for a probable inversion for the p-nuclei 130Ba and 132Ba).
[src:ferrite-magnet/barium] In total, barium has 41 known isotopes, ranging in mass between 114 and 154.
[src:ferrite-magnet/barium] The most stable artificial radioisotope is barium-133 with a half-life of 10.538 years.
[src:ferrite-magnet/barium] Five other isotopes have half-lives longer than a day.
[src:ferrite-magnet/barium] The longest-lived isomers are 133mBa at 38.90 hours and 135m1Ba at 28.11 hours.
[src:ferrite-magnet/barium] The analogous 137m1Ba (half-life 2.552 minutes) occurs in the decay of the common fission product caesium-137.
[src:ferrite-magnet/barium] Alchemists in the early Middle Ages knew about some barium minerals.
[src:ferrite-magnet/barium] Smooth pebble-like stones of mineral baryte were found in volcanic rock near Bologna, Italy, and so were called "Bologna stones".
[src:ferrite-magnet/barium] Alchemists were attracted to them because after exposure to light they would glow for years.
[src:ferrite-magnet/barium] The phosphorescent properties of baryte heated with organics were described by V.
[src:ferrite-magnet/barium] Carl Scheele determined that baryte contained a new element in 1772, but could not isolate barium, only barium oxide.
[src:ferrite-magnet/barium] Johan Gottlieb Gahn also isolated barium oxide two years later in similar studies.
[src:ferrite-magnet/barium] Oxidized barium was at first called "barote" by Guyton de Morveau, a name that was changed by Antoine Lavoisier to *baryte* (in French) or *baryta* (in Latin).
[src:ferrite-magnet/barium] Also in the 18th century, English mineralogist William Withering noted a heavy mineral in the lead mines of Cumberland, now known to be witherite.
[src:ferrite-magnet/barium] Barium was first isolated by electrolysis of molten barium salts in 1808 by Sir Humphry Davy in England.
[src:ferrite-magnet/barium] Davy, by analogy with calcium, named "barium" after baryta, with the "-ium" ending signifying a metallic element.
[src:ferrite-magnet/barium] Robert Bunsen and Augustus Matthiessen obtained pure barium by electrolysis of a molten mixture of barium chloride and ammonium chloride.
[src:ferrite-magnet/barium] The production of pure oxygen in the Brin process was a large-scale application of barium peroxide in the 1880s, before it was replaced by electrolysis and fractional distillation of liquefied air in the early 1900s.
[src:ferrite-magnet/barium] Barium sulfate was first applied as a radiocontrast agent in X-ray imaging of the digestive system in 1908.
[src:ferrite-magnet/barium] The abundance of barium is 0.0425% in the Earth's crust and 13 μg/L in sea water.
[src:ferrite-magnet/barium] The primary commercial source of barium is baryte (also called barytes or heavy spar), a barium sulfate mineral. with deposits in many parts of the world.
[src:ferrite-magnet/barium] Another commercial source, far less important than baryte, is witherite, barium carbonate.
[src:ferrite-magnet/barium] The main deposits are located in Britain, Romania, and the former USSR.
[src:ferrite-magnet/barium] Barite, left to right: appearance, graph showing trends in production over time, and the map showing shares of the most important producer countries in 2010.
[src:ferrite-magnet/barium] The baryte reserves are estimated between 0.7 and 2 billion tonnes.
[src:ferrite-magnet/barium] The highest production, 8.3 million tonnes, was achieved in 1981, but only 7–8% was used for barium metal or compounds.
[src:ferrite-magnet/barium] Baryte production has risen since the second half of the 1990s from 5.6 million tonnes in 1996 to 7.6 in 2005 and 7.8 in 2011.
[src:ferrite-magnet/barium] China accounts for more than 50% of this output, followed by India (14% in 2011), Morocco (8.3%), US (8.2%), Iran and Kazakhstan (2.6% each) and Turkey (2.5%).
[src:ferrite-magnet/barium] The mined ore is washed, crushed, classified, and separated from quartz.
[src:ferrite-magnet/barium] If the quartz penetrates too deeply into the ore, or the iron, zinc, or lead content is abnormally high, then froth flotation is used.
[src:ferrite-magnet/barium] The product is a 98% pure baryte (by mass); the purity should be no less than 95%, with a minimal content of iron and silicon dioxide.
[src:ferrite-magnet/barium] The water-soluble barium sulfide is the starting point for other compounds: treating BaS with oxygen produces the sulfate, with nitric acid the nitrate, with aqueous carbon dioxide the carbonate, and so on.
[src:ferrite-magnet/barium] The nitrate can be thermally decomposed to yield the oxide.
[src:ferrite-magnet/barium] Barium metal is produced by reduction with aluminium at 1,100 °C (2,010 °F).
[src:ferrite-magnet/barium] The remaining barium oxide reacts with the aluminium oxide formed...
[src:ferrite-magnet/barium] Barium vapor is condensed and packed into molds in an atmosphere of argon.
[src:ferrite-magnet/barium] This method is used commercially, yielding ultrapure barium.
[src:ferrite-magnet/barium] Commonly sold barium is about 99% pure, with main impurities being strontium and calcium (up to 0.8% and 0.25%) and other contaminants contributing less than 0.1%.
[src:ferrite-magnet/barium] A similar reaction with silicon at 1,200 °C (2,190 °F) yields barium and barium metasilicate.
[src:ferrite-magnet/barium] Electrolysis is not used because barium readily dissolves in molten halides and the product is rather impure.
[src:ferrite-magnet/barium] The barium mineral, benitoite (barium titanium silicate), occurs as a very rare blue fluorescent gemstone, and is the official state gem of California.
[src:ferrite-magnet/barium] Barium exists in seawater as the Ba2+ ion with an average oceanic concentration of 109 nmol/kg.
[src:ferrite-magnet/barium] Barium also exists in the ocean as BaSO4, or barite.
[src:ferrite-magnet/barium] Barium has a nutrient-like profile with a residence time of 10,000 years.
[src:ferrite-magnet/barium] Barium shows a relatively consistent concentration in upper ocean seawater, excepting regions of high river inputs and regions with strong upwelling.
[src:ferrite-magnet/barium] There is little depletion of barium concentrations in the upper ocean for an ion with a nutrient-like profile, thus lateral mixing is important.
[src:ferrite-magnet/barium] Barium isotopic values show basin-scale balances instead of local or short-term processes.
[src:ferrite-magnet/barium] Barium, as a metal or when alloyed with aluminium, is used to remove unwanted gases (gettering) from vacuum tubes, such as TV picture tubes.
[src:ferrite-magnet/barium] Barium is suitable for this purpose because of its low vapor pressure and reactivity towards oxygen, nitrogen, carbon dioxide, and water; it can even partly remove noble gases by dissolving them in the crystal lattice.
[src:ferrite-magnet/barium] This application has gradually disappeared due to the popularity of the tubeless LCD, LED, and plasma sets.
[src:ferrite-magnet/barium] Barium sulfate (the mineral baryte, BaSO4) is important to the petroleum industry as a drilling fluid in oil and gas wells.
[src:ferrite-magnet/barium] The precipitate of the compound (called "blanc fixe", from the French for "permanent white") is used in paints and varnishes; as a filler in ringing ink, plastics, and rubbers; as a paper coating pigment; and in nanoparticles, to improve physical properties of some polymers, such as epoxies.
[src:ferrite-magnet/barium] Barium sulfate has a low toxicity and relatively high density of ca.
[src:ferrite-magnet/barium] For this reason it is used as a radiocontrast agent in X-ray imaging of the digestive system ("barium meals" and "barium enemas").
[src:ferrite-magnet/barium] Lithopone, a pigment that contains barium sulfate and zinc sulfide, is a permanent white with good covering power that does not darken when exposed to sulfides.
[src:ferrite-magnet/barium] Other compounds of barium find only niche applications, limited by the toxicity of Ba2+ ions , which is not a problem for the insoluble BaSO4.
[src:ferrite-magnet/barium] The lateral mixing of barium is caused by water mass mixing and ocean circulation.
[src:ferrite-magnet/barium] Global ocean circulation reveals a strong correlation between dissolved barium and silicic acid.
[src:ferrite-magnet/barium] The large-scale ocean circulation combined with remineralization of barium show a similar correlation between dissolved barium and ocean alkalinity.
[src:ferrite-magnet/barium] Dissolved barium's correlation with silicic acid can be seen both vertically and spatially.
[src:ferrite-magnet/barium] Particulate barium shows a strong correlation with particulate organic carbon or POC.
[src:ferrite-magnet/barium] Barium is becoming more popular as a base for palaeoceanographic proxies.
[src:ferrite-magnet/barium] With both dissolved and particulate barium's links with silicic acid and POC, it can be used to determine historical variations in the biological pump, carbon cycle, and global climate.
[src:ferrite-magnet/barium] The barium particulate barite (BaSO4), as one of many proxies, can be used to provide a host of historical information on processes in different oceanic settings (water column, sediments, and hydrothermal sites).
[src:ferrite-magnet/barium] In each setting there are differences in isotopic and elemental composition of the barite particulate.
[src:ferrite-magnet/barium] Barite in the water column, known as marine or pelagic barite, reveals information on seawater chemistry variation over time.
[src:ferrite-magnet/barium] Barite in sediments, known as diagenetic or cold seeps barite, gives information about sedimentary redox processes.
[src:ferrite-magnet/barium] Barite formed via hydrothermal activity at hydrothermal vents, known as hydrothermal barite, reveals alterations in the condition of the earth's crust around those vents.
[src:ferrite-magnet/barium] Soluble barium compounds have an LD50 near 10 mg/kg (oral, rats).
[src:ferrite-magnet/barium] Symptoms include "convulsions... paralysis of the peripheral nerve system ... severe inflammation of the gastrointestinal tract".
[src:ferrite-magnet/barium] The insoluble sulfate is nontoxic and is not classified as a dangerous goods in transport regulations.
[src:ferrite-magnet/barium] Little is known about the long term effects of barium exposure.
[src:ferrite-magnet/barium] The US EPA considers it unlikely that barium is carcinogenic when consumed orally.
[src:ferrite-magnet/barium] Inhaled dust containing insoluble barium compounds can accumulate in the lungs, causing a benign condition called baritosis.
[src:ferrite-magnet/barium] Barium carbonate has been used as a rodenticide.
[src:ferrite-magnet/barium] Though considered obsolete, it may still be in use in some countries.
[src:ferrite-magnet/ferrite-magnet] A **ferrite** is one of a family of iron-oxide-containing magnetic ceramic materials.
[src:ferrite-magnet/ferrite-magnet] They are ferrimagnetic, meaning they are attracted by magnetic fields and can be magnetized to become permanent magnets.
[src:ferrite-magnet/ferrite-magnet] Unlike many ferromagnetic materials, most ferrites are not electrically-conductive, making them useful in applications like magnetic cores for transformers to suppress eddy currents.
[src:ferrite-magnet/ferrite-magnet] Ferrites can be divided into two groups based on their magnetic coercivity, their resistance to being demagnetized: **"Hard" ferrites** have high coercivity, so are difficult to demagnetize.
[src:ferrite-magnet/ferrite-magnet] They are used to make permanent magnets for applications such as refrigerator magnets, loudspeakers, and small electric motors.
[src:ferrite-magnet/ferrite-magnet] **"Soft" ferrites** have low coercivity, so they easily change their magnetization and act as conductors of magnetic fields.
[src:ferrite-magnet/ferrite-magnet] They are used in the electronics industry to make efficient magnetic cores called ferrite cores for high-frequency inductors, transformers and antennas, and in various microwave components.
[src:ferrite-magnet/ferrite-magnet] Ferrite compounds are extremely low cost, being made mostly of iron oxide, and have excellent corrosion resistance.
[src:ferrite-magnet/ferrite-magnet] Yogoro Kato and Takeshi Takei of the Tokyo Institute of Technology synthesized the first ferrite compounds in 1930.
[src:ferrite-magnet/ferrite-magnet] Ferrites are usually ferrimagnetic ceramic compounds derived from iron oxides, with either a body-centered cubic or hexagonal crystal structure.
[src:ferrite-magnet/ferrite-magnet] Like most of the other ceramics, ferrites are hard, brittle, and poor conductors of electricity.
[src:ferrite-magnet/ferrite-magnet] They are typically composed of α-iron(III) oxide (e.g. hematite Fe2O3) with one, or more additional, metallic element oxides, usually with an approximately stoichiometric formula of *M*O·Fe2O3 such as Fe(II) such as in the common mineral magnetite composed of Fe(II)-Fe(III)2O4.
[src:ferrite-magnet/ferrite-magnet] Above 585 °C Fe(II)-Fe(III)2O4 transforms into the non-magnetic gamma phase.
[src:ferrite-magnet/ferrite-magnet] Fe(II)-Fe(III)2O4 is commonly seen as the black iron(II) oxide coating the surface of cast-iron cookware).
[src:ferrite-magnet/ferrite-magnet] The other pattern is *M*·Fe(III)2O3, where *M* is another metallic element.
[src:ferrite-magnet/ferrite-magnet] Common, naturally occurring ferrites (typically members of the spinel group) include those with nickel (NiFe2O4) which occurs as the mineral trevorite, magnesium containing magnesioferrite (MgFe2O4), cobalt (cobalt ferrite), or manganese (MnFe2O4) which occurs naturally as the mineral jacobsite.
[src:ferrite-magnet/ferrite-magnet] Less often bismuth, strontium, zinc as found in franklinite, aluminum,yittrium, or barium ferrites are used In addition, more complex synthetic alloys are often used for specific applications.
[src:ferrite-magnet/ferrite-magnet] Many ferrites adopt the spinel chemical structure with the formula **AB** 2O 4, where **A** and **B** represent various metal cations, one of which is usually iron (Fe).
[src:ferrite-magnet/ferrite-magnet] Spinel ferrites usually adopt a crystal motif consisting of cubic close-packed (fcc) oxides (O2−) with **A** cations occupying one eighth of the tetrahedral holes, and **B** cations occupying half of the octahedral holes, i.e., **A**2+ **B**3+ 2O2− 4.
[src:ferrite-magnet/ferrite-magnet] An exception exists for ɣ-Fe2O3 which has a spinel crystalline form and is widely used a magnetic recording substrate.
[src:ferrite-magnet/ferrite-magnet] However the structure is not an ordinary spinel structure, but rather the inverse spinel structure: One eighth of the tetrahedral holes are occupied by **B** cations, one fourth of the octahedral sites are occupied by **A** cations. and the other one fourth by **B** cation.
[src:ferrite-magnet/ferrite-magnet] It is also possible to have mixed structure spinel ferrites with formula [**M**2+ (1−*δ*) Fe3+ δ ] [**M**2+ δ Fe3+ (2−*δ*) ] O 4, where δ is the degree of inversion.
[src:ferrite-magnet/ferrite-magnet] The magnetic material known as "Zn Fe" has the formula ZnFe 2O 4, with Fe3+ occupying the octahedral sites and Zn2+ occupying the tetrahedral sites, it is an example of normal structure spinel ferrite.
[src:ferrite-magnet/ferrite-magnet] Some ferrites adopt hexagonal crystal structure, like barium and strontium ferrites BaFe 12O 19 (BaO·6Fe 2O 3 ) and SrFe 12O 19 (SrO·6Fe 2O 3 ).
[src:ferrite-magnet/ferrite-magnet] In terms of their magnetic properties, the different ferrites are often classified as "soft", "semi-hard" or "hard", which refers to their low or high magnetic coercivity, as follows.
[src:ferrite-magnet/ferrite-magnet] Ferrites that are used in transformer or electromagnetic cores contain nickel, zinc, and/or manganese compounds.
[src:ferrite-magnet/ferrite-magnet] Soft ferrites are not suitable to make permanent magnets.
[src:ferrite-magnet/ferrite-magnet] They have high magnetic permeability so they conduct magnetic fields and are attracted to magnets, but when the external magnetic field is removed, the remanent magnetization does not tend to persist.
[src:ferrite-magnet/ferrite-magnet] The low coercivity also means the material's magnetization can easily reverse direction without dissipating much energy (hysteresis losses), while the material's high resistivity prevents eddy currents in the core, another source of energy loss.
[src:ferrite-magnet/ferrite-magnet] Because of their comparatively low core losses at high frequencies, they are extensively used in the cores of RF transformers and inductors in applications such as switched-mode power supplies and loopstick antennas used in AM radios.
[src:ferrite-magnet/ferrite-magnet] Ni Zn ferrites exhibit higher resistivity than Mn Zn, and are therefore more suitable for frequencies above 1 MHz.
[src:ferrite-magnet/ferrite-magnet] For use with frequencies above 0.5 MHz but below 5 MHz, Mn Zn ferrites are used; above that, Ni Zn is the usual choice.
[src:ferrite-magnet/ferrite-magnet] The exception is with common mode inductors, where the threshold of choice is at 70 MHz.
[src:ferrite-magnet/ferrite-magnet] ) is in between soft and hard magnetic material and is usually classified as a semi-hard material.
[src:ferrite-magnet/ferrite-magnet] Moreover, cobalt ferrite's magnetostrictive properties can be tuned by inducing a magnetic uniaxial anisotropy.
[src:ferrite-magnet/ferrite-magnet] This can be done by magnetic annealing, magnetic field assisted compaction, or reaction under uniaxial pressure.
[src:ferrite-magnet/ferrite-magnet] This last solution has the advantage to be ultra fast (20 min) thanks to the use of spark plasma sintering.
[src:ferrite-magnet/ferrite-magnet] The induced magnetic anisotropy in cobalt ferrite is also beneficial to enhance the magnetoelectric effect in composite.
[src:ferrite-magnet/ferrite-magnet] In contrast, permanent ferrite magnets are made of **hard ferrites**, which have a high coercivity and high remanence after magnetization.
[src:ferrite-magnet/ferrite-magnet] The high coercivity means the materials are very resistant to becoming demagnetized, an essential characteristic for a permanent magnet.
[src:ferrite-magnet/ferrite-magnet] They also have high magnetic permeability.
[src:ferrite-magnet/ferrite-magnet] These so-called *ceramic magnets* are cheap, and are widely used in household products such as refrigerator magnets.
[src:ferrite-magnet/ferrite-magnet] The maximum magnetic field B is about 0.35 tesla and the magnetic field strength H is about 30–160 kiloampere turns per meter (400–2000 oersteds).
[src:ferrite-magnet/ferrite-magnet] The density of ferrite magnets is about 5 g/cm3.
[src:ferrite-magnet/ferrite-magnet] ), used in small electric motors, micro-wave devices, recording media, magneto-optic media, telecommunication, and electronics industry.
[src:ferrite-magnet/ferrite-magnet] due to its magnetocrystalline anisotropy.
[src:ferrite-magnet/ferrite-magnet] It has been widely used in industrial applications as permanent magnets and, because they can be powdered and formed easily, they are finding their applications into micro and nano-types systems such as biomarkers, bio diagnostics and biosensors.
[src:ferrite-magnet/ferrite-magnet] ), a common material for permanent magnet applications.
[src:ferrite-magnet/ferrite-magnet] Barium ferrites are robust ceramics that are generally stable to moisture and corrosion-resistant.
[src:ferrite-magnet/ferrite-magnet] Iron oxide and (barium carbonate or strontium carbonate) are used in manufacturing of hard ferrite magnets.
[src:ferrite-magnet/ferrite-magnet] Ferrites are mainly produced by two main processes: co-precipitation or the sol-gel process.
[src:ferrite-magnet/ferrite-magnet] Both processes start with an aqueous solution.
[src:ferrite-magnet/ferrite-magnet] The addition of a base/acid (co-precipitation) or a fuel/chelate (sol-gel) initiates the transformation of the solution.
[src:ferrite-magnet/ferrite-magnet] In co-precipitation, metallic ions form hydroxide/oxide precipitates.
[src:ferrite-magnet/ferrite-magnet] After filtering, washing, drying, and grinding, the powder is calcined to obtain the ferrite phase.
[src:ferrite-magnet/ferrite-magnet] In some cases, the mixture of finely-powdered precursors is pressed into a mold.
[src:ferrite-magnet/ferrite-magnet] For barium and strontium ferrites, these metals are typically supplied as their carbonates, BaCO3 or SrCO3.
[src:ferrite-magnet/ferrite-magnet] After this step, the two oxides combine to give the ferrite.
[src:ferrite-magnet/ferrite-magnet] The resulting mixture of oxides undergoes sintering.
[src:ferrite-magnet/ferrite-magnet] Having obtained the ferrite, the cooled product is milled to particles smaller than 2 μm, sufficiently small that each particle consists of a single magnetic domain.
[src:ferrite-magnet/ferrite-magnet] Next the powder is pressed into a shape, dried, and re-sintered.
[src:ferrite-magnet/ferrite-magnet] The shaping may be performed in an external magnetic field, in order to achieve a preferred orientation of the particles (anisotropy).
[src:ferrite-magnet/ferrite-magnet] Small and geometrically easy shapes may be produced with dry pressing.
[src:ferrite-magnet/ferrite-magnet] However, in such a process small particles may agglomerate and lead to poorer magnetic properties compared to the wet pressing process.
[src:ferrite-magnet/ferrite-magnet] Direct calcination and sintering without re-milling is possible as well but leads to poor magnetic properties.
[src:ferrite-magnet/ferrite-magnet] Ferrite cores for electromagnets can be pre-sintered as well (pre-reaction), milled and pressed.
[src:ferrite-magnet/ferrite-magnet] However, the sintering takes place in a specific atmosphere, for instance one with an oxygen shortage.
[src:ferrite-magnet/ferrite-magnet] The chemical composition and especially the structure vary strongly between the precursor and the sintered product.
[src:ferrite-magnet/ferrite-magnet] To allow efficient stacking of product in the furnace during sintering and prevent parts sticking together, many manufacturers separate ware using ceramic powder separator sheets.
[src:ferrite-magnet/ferrite-magnet] These sheets are available in various materials such as alumina, zirconia and magnesia.
[src:ferrite-magnet/ferrite-magnet] They are also available in fine, medium and coarse particle sizes.
[src:ferrite-magnet/ferrite-magnet] By matching the material and particle size to the ware being sintered, surface damage and contamination can be reduced while maximizing furnace loading.
[src:ferrite-magnet/ferrite-magnet] Ferrite cores are used in electronic inductors, transformers, and electromagnets where the high electrical resistance of the ferrite leads to very low eddy current losses.
[src:ferrite-magnet/ferrite-magnet] Early computer memories stored data in the residual magnetic fields of hard ferrite cores, which were assembled into arrays of *core memory*.
[src:ferrite-magnet/ferrite-magnet] Ferrite powders are used in the coatings of magnetic recording tapes.
[src:ferrite-magnet/ferrite-magnet] Ferrite particles are also used as a component of radar-absorbing materials or coatings used in stealth aircraft and in the absorption tiles lining the rooms used for electromagnetic compatibility measurements.
[src:ferrite-magnet/ferrite-magnet] Most common audio magnets, including those used in loudspeakers and electromagnetic instrument pickups, are ferrite magnets.
[src:ferrite-magnet/ferrite-magnet] Except for certain "vintage" products, ferrite magnets have largely displaced the more expensive Alnico magnets in these applications.
[src:ferrite-magnet/ferrite-magnet] In particular, for hard hexaferrites today the most-common uses are still as permanent magnets in refrigerator seal gaskets, microphones and loudspeakers, small motors for cordless appliances, and in automobile applications.
[src:ferrite-magnet/ferrite-magnet] Ferrite magnets find applications in electric power steering systems and automotive sensors due to their cost-effectiveness and corrosion resistance.
[src:ferrite-magnet/ferrite-magnet] Ferrite magnets are known for their high magnetic permeability and low electrical conductivity, making them suitable for high-frequency applications.
[src:ferrite-magnet/ferrite-magnet] In electric power steering systems, they provide the necessary magnetic field for efficient motor operation, contributing to the system's overall performance and reliability.
[src:ferrite-magnet/ferrite-magnet] Automotive sensors utilize ferrite magnets for accurate detection and measurement of various parameters, such as position, speed, and fluid levels.
[src:ferrite-magnet/ferrite-magnet] Due to ceramic ferrite magnet's weaker magnetic fields compared to superconducting magnets, they are sometimes used in low-field or open MRI systems.
[src:ferrite-magnet/ferrite-magnet] These magnets are favored in certain cases due to their lower cost, stable magnetic field, and ability to function without the need for complex cooling systems.
[src:ferrite-magnet/ferrite-magnet] Ferrite nanoparticles exhibit superparamagnetic properties.
[src:ferrite-magnet/ferrite-magnet] This led to the founding of TDK Corporation in 1935, to manufacture the material.
[src:ferrite-magnet/ferrite-magnet] Barium hexaferrite (BaO•6Fe2O3) was discovered in 1950 at the Philips Natuurkundig Laboratorium (*Philips Physics Laboratory*).
[src:ferrite-magnet/ferrite-magnet] The discovery was somewhat accidental—due to a mistake by an assistant who was supposed to be preparing a sample of hexagonal lanthanum ferrite for a team investigating its use as a semiconductor material.
[src:ferrite-magnet/ferrite-magnet] On discovering that it was actually a magnetic material, and confirming its structure by X-ray crystallography, they passed it on to the magnetic research group.
[src:ferrite-magnet/ferrite-magnet] Barium hexaferrite has both high coercivity (170 kA/m) and low raw material costs.
[src:ferrite-magnet/ferrite-magnet] It was developed as a product by Philips Industries (Netherlands) and from 1952 was marketed under the trade name *Ferroxdure*.
[src:ferrite-magnet/ferrite-magnet] The low price and good performance led to a rapid increase in the use of permanent magnets.
[src:ferrite-magnet/ferrite-magnet] In the 1960s Philips developed strontium hexaferrite (SrO•6Fe2O3), with better properties than barium hexaferrite.
[src:ferrite-magnet/ferrite-magnet] Barium and strontium hexaferrite dominate the market due to their low costs.
[src:ferrite-magnet/ferrite-magnet] Other materials have been found with improved properties.
